WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I. V. M.

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:06.400
[Amit Varma]: I had a strange dream the other day.

00:00:06.700 --> 00:00:08.700
[Amit Varma]: I dreamed that I was 700 years old.

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:14.400
[Amit Varma]: I was in a courtroom fighting a case that had been going on for the last 680 years.

00:00:14.900 --> 00:00:16.900
[Amit Varma]: I begged the judge for a judgment.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:19.800
[Amit Varma]: I've been waiting so long, I told him.

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:23.700
[Amit Varma]: It's been more than 600 years. Please put me out of my misery.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:25.200
[Amit Varma]: Deliver a judgment.

00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:27.400
[Amit Varma]: The judge looked at me and said,

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:33.900
[Amit Varma]: Oh, I can deliver a judgment, but then this case will go to appeals and that will take another 700 years.

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:36.900
[Amit Varma]: What's your life span anyway, Mr. Verma?

00:00:37.200 --> 00:00:38.900
[Amit Varma]: How long do you want to live?

00:00:39.400 --> 00:00:42.400
[Amit Varma]: Forever, I said. I will wait forever.

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:44.400
[Amit Varma]: What choice do I have?

00:00:47.400 --> 00:00:49.400
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen,

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:53.400
[Unknown]: our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science.

00:00:53.400 --> 00:00:56.900
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:00:57.900 --> 00:00:59.900
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:00.400 --> 00:01:03.900
[Amit Varma]: None of us need to be told that our country's judicial system is in a mess.

00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:06.900
[Amit Varma]: Cases drag on for years and decades,

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:09.900
[Amit Varma]: and I've actually heard of a case which is more than a few hundred years old.

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:11.900
[Amit Varma]: Don't ask me how that happened.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:15.900
[Amit Varma]: So the subject for this episode, therefore, is judicial reforms.

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:19.900
[Amit Varma]: And to help me make sense of all the ways in which our judicial system is messed up

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:21.900
[Amit Varma]: and all that we can do about it,

00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:25.400
[Amit Varma]: I have with me as my guest, my friend Alok Prasanna Kumar,

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:31.400
[Amit Varma]: who is a senior fellow and heads a Bangalore office of the Vidhi Centre for Legal Policy.

00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:34.400
[Amit Varma]: We had this conversation a couple of weeks ago in Bangalore.

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Alok, thanks so much for coming on The Seen and The Unseen.

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:40.400
[Amit Varma]: My pleasure, Amit.

00:01:40.900 --> 00:01:43.400
[Amit Varma]: Alok, all of us know that the judiciary is in need of reform.

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:46.400
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to come at this episode from a complete layman's point of view.

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:49.400
[Amit Varma]: What we typically know about the judiciary is, you know,

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:51.900
[Amit Varma]: you get those Bollywood dialogues of Tariq pe Tariq, Tariq pe Tariq.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:53.900
[Amit Varma]: We know it's overburdened.

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:56.900
[Amit Varma]: We know that under trials stay in prison for decades sometimes.

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:00.900
[Amit Varma]: And we know that cases just linger for literally hundreds of years.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:03.900
[Amit Varma]: I mean, someone was telling me the oldest case is some 700 years old

00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:05.900
[Amit Varma]: and it's just continuing through all these ages.

00:02:06.400 --> 00:02:08.900
[Amit Varma]: What I want you to do today in the course of this conversation is,

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:12.900
[Amit Varma]: number one, actually define what is the scope of the problem?

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:14.900
[Unknown]: What caused it?

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:16.900
[Amit Varma]: What can we do about it?

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:19.400
[Amit Varma]: And how hard is it to carry out those reforms?

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:20.400
[Guest]: Okay.

00:02:20.900 --> 00:02:23.400
[Guest]: So, defining the scope of the problem.

00:02:23.900 --> 00:02:26.400
[Guest]: When we say the judiciary, there is no one wing of the judiciary

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:28.400
[Guest]: which is not free of this problem.

00:02:28.900 --> 00:02:32.400
[Guest]: We have the same kinds of problems happening at all levels.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:37.400
[Guest]: And there are multiple problems.

00:02:37.900 --> 00:02:40.400
[Guest]: I think some are problems with the institution itself as it stands.

00:02:40.900 --> 00:02:45.400
[Guest]: We have not really moved away from the 19th century notion

00:02:45.400 --> 00:02:46.900
[Guest]: of what a judiciary should be.

00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:51.900
[Guest]: We have added computers and possibly used nice fonts in our pleadings.

00:02:52.400 --> 00:02:53.900
[Guest]: But our notion of how the judiciary should function

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:57.900
[Guest]: still harks back to the 19th century House of Lords.

00:02:58.400 --> 00:02:59.900
[Guest]: And the structure of the judiciary follows

00:03:00.400 --> 00:03:03.900
[Guest]: is almost similar to what the British had set up.

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:05.900
[Guest]: The only difference being that the subordinate judiciary

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:07.900
[Guest]: is not under the control of the state government.

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:09.900
[Guest]: So what is that 19th century notion?

00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:11.900
[Guest]: The 19th century notion is that you have people

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:13.900
[Guest]: who want to file voluminous pleadings,

00:03:13.900 --> 00:03:16.400
[Guest]: who are happy to engage in litigation as long as they want.

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:18.400
[Guest]: And the court's job is not to tell them to move on quickly,

00:03:18.900 --> 00:03:20.400
[Guest]: but let parties take their own time

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:22.400
[Guest]: and you figure out how to decide the cases.

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:28.400
[Guest]: Judgments are delivered, of course, in accordance with the law, obviously,

00:03:28.900 --> 00:03:34.400
[Guest]: but this is what the institution should work like.

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:38.400
[Guest]: It still follows the approach that people will decide

00:03:38.900 --> 00:03:40.400
[Guest]: how they want to litigate a case.

00:03:40.400 --> 00:03:43.900
[Guest]: Their job is only to, as with a baseball umpire,

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:45.900
[Guest]: call the pitches and call the strikers.

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:47.900
[Guest]: And there's a reason why I'm using baseball

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:52.900
[Guest]: because in baseball, the umpire's role is relatively much smaller

00:03:53.400 --> 00:03:54.900
[Guest]: than the role of an umpire in cricket.

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:57.900
[Guest]: In cricket, there are subjective calls that the umpire makes.

00:03:58.400 --> 00:03:58.900
[Guest]: Umpire speeds up the game.

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:00.900
[Guest]: Umpire can say, okay, you're taking too much time.

00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:02.900
[Guest]: Move quickly, move quickly or I'll penalize you in this way.

00:04:03.400 --> 00:04:05.900
[Guest]: So ironically, even though we got cricket from the Brits,

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:08.900
[Guest]: we haven't adopted that approach in our judiciary at all.

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:12.400
[Guest]: So we are still content at letting the judge be somebody who says,

00:04:12.900 --> 00:04:15.400
[Guest]: fine, you want to file one more document, take some more time.

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:17.400
[Guest]: Fine, you want an adjournment, take your time.

00:04:17.900 --> 00:04:18.400
[Amit Varma]: Do this, that.

00:04:18.900 --> 00:04:19.400
[Amit Varma]: That's the basic level of support.

00:04:19.900 --> 00:04:21.400
[Amit Varma]: So what do you think the 19th century notion, therefore,

00:04:21.900 --> 00:04:23.400
[Amit Varma]: is that the judge is only interested in the final outcome

00:04:23.900 --> 00:04:26.400
[Guest]: and doesn't interfere much with the smoothening of the process?

00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:27.400
[Guest]: No, it isn't.

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:30.400
[Guest]: And the idea is that the process is something

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:34.400
[Guest]: which broadly meets the requirements of the natural justice,

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:37.400
[Guest]: but we have to hold them to the process.

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:38.900
[Guest]: If somebody needs time to file this document,

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:40.900
[Guest]: the other person has to be given time to respond to this.

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:43.900
[Guest]: Then the other person has to be able to allow to do this.

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:45.900
[Guest]: Our code of civil procedure was drafted

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:47.900
[Guest]: in the first decade of the 20th century.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:49.900
[Guest]: We have made no major amendments to it.

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:51.900
[Guest]: The one effort at trying to make an amendment

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:53.900
[Guest]: was rolled back almost instantly.

00:04:54.400 --> 00:04:56.900
[Guest]: So we are still stuck with this old notions

00:04:57.400 --> 00:04:58.900
[Guest]: of how a case should move through the court,

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:00.900
[Guest]: whereas the rest of the world has moved on.

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:02.900
[Guest]: Even Britain has moved on.

00:05:03.400 --> 00:05:05.900
[Guest]: Even they have understood that cases have to follow

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:08.400
[Guest]: a certain approach in terms of

00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:11.400
[Guest]: they need to be done by this period of time, right?

00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:13.400
[Guest]: And it's in the hands of the judge

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:15.400
[Guest]: to ensure that it's done in this period of time.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:17.400
[Guest]: The judge is a person now responsible for seeing a case through,

00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:19.400
[Guest]: not up to the parties.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:21.400
[Guest]: So the judge will say, look, I'm giving you this much time.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:23.400
[Guest]: You have to do whatever you need to do in this time.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:25.400
[Guest]: I'll fix it for arguments.

00:05:25.900 --> 00:05:27.400
[Guest]: And I want you to finish your arguments by this period of time.

00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:29.400
[Guest]: And I'm delivering judgment.

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:31.400
[Guest]: All these countries have realized that

00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:33.400
[Guest]: there is a certain point of time where you just can't keep adding

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:35.900
[Guest]: capacity to the judiciary and hoping that everything will continue as normal.

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:38.900
[Guest]: They've all recognized that it works.

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:40.900
[Guest]: The judiciary as understood in the 19th century model judiciary

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:42.900
[Guest]: is extremely inefficient.

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:44.900
[Guest]: It's extremely inefficient.

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:46.900
[Guest]: It is not geared towards quick disposal of cases.

00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:49.900
[Guest]: Yes, parties will be convinced of the court's independence,

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:51.900
[Guest]: but the fact is there's only a certain price

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:54.900
[Guest]: that are willing to pay to wait for the judgment to come eventually.

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:56.900
[Amit Varma]: So as an old cliche goes,

00:05:57.400 --> 00:05:58.900
[Amit Varma]: justice delayed and justice denied and so on.

00:05:59.400 --> 00:06:01.900
[Amit Varma]: So what you'd say is that the 21st century mode of justice

00:06:01.900 --> 00:06:05.400
[Amit Varma]: pays a lot of importance to the process so that justice is not delayed.

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:06.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And is this sort of a necessity brought about

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:12.400
[Amit Varma]: by the sheer volume of cases and litigants

00:06:12.900 --> 00:06:14.400
[Amit Varma]: that of course happens with the growing population

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:19.400
[Amit Varma]: or would you say that it is part of the better delivery of justice as well?

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:21.400
[Guest]: It's, it's also, it's, it's a bit of both.

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:24.400
[Guest]: Now, in terms of actual number of cases,

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:26.400
[Guest]: India probably doesn't have as many as the US.

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:27.400
[Guest]: Wow.

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:30.400
[Guest]: I mean, it's hard to compare one to one,

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:34.900
[Guest]: but the volume of litigation probably is less in India than in the US as well.

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:38.900
[Guest]: Because the other factor for growth of population is economic growth.

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:40.900
[Guest]: So which means you have more entities,

00:06:41.400 --> 00:06:42.900
[Guest]: you have companies filing trusts, filing societies,

00:06:43.400 --> 00:06:44.900
[Guest]: filing cases against each other and so on.

00:06:45.400 --> 00:06:49.900
[Guest]: But also the fact that we have not seen the justice delivery as a service.

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:54.900
[Guest]: We've just seen us as this big institution sitting in the old sandstone

00:06:55.400 --> 00:06:56.900
[Guest]: that is immovable and whatever.

00:06:56.900 --> 00:07:00.400
[Guest]: And we've never thought of what goes on inside that institution.

00:07:00.900 --> 00:07:04.400
[Guest]: How are cases taken on board, listed, heard, disposed of?

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:06.400
[Guest]: We've never really thought about it seriously.

00:07:06.900 --> 00:07:08.400
[Guest]: And only now that people are realizing, oh, hang on, you know,

00:07:08.900 --> 00:07:10.400
[Guest]: we should start looking into the processes of the judiciary

00:07:10.900 --> 00:07:13.400
[Guest]: and realizing that, oh, well, there's no way, you know,

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:15.400
[Guest]: if this was a process in any private company,

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:18.400
[Guest]: it would have collapsed in a matter of months because nothing happens.

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.400
[Guest]: So, which is why I think we have not seen it in those terms.

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:25.400
[Guest]: And the pity is it, this whole argument of first world judiciary

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:26.900
[Guest]: and so on and stuff doesn't really hold

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:30.900
[Guest]: because you have an excellent model just across the Andaman Sea.

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:36.900
[Guest]: Singapore, for instance, is truly the beneficiary of India's failing judicial system.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:38.900
[Guest]: Some of the highest value arbitration,

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.900
[Guest]: some of the most important commercial cases go to Singapore.

00:07:42.400 --> 00:07:43.900
[Guest]: Greatest example, Ranbaxy.

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:45.900
[Guest]: Ranbaxy and Daichi sank your case, went to Singapore Arbitral Tribunal.

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:48.900
[Guest]: Why? Because the parties are sure that in Singapore,

00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:50.900
[Guest]: when you arbitrate a case, it's done within a year.

00:07:51.400 --> 00:07:53.900
[Guest]: When you challenge it in court, it's done within a fixed period of time.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:57.400
[Guest]: And when you challenge it even further, that also has a fixed period of time.

00:07:57.900 --> 00:08:00.400
[Amit Varma]: So, therefore, both parties recognize that closure is important, has value,

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.400
[Amit Varma]: and that delays are a negative sum game.

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.400
[Amit Varma]: Both parties heard, so let's just go to Singapore, get it sorted out quickly.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:07.400
[Amit Varma]: Whoever loses, loses.

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:10.400
[Amit Varma]: So, my question is that this 19th century mode of thinking, as you're saying,

00:08:10.900 --> 00:08:14.400
[Amit Varma]: is it embedded in the laws and the rules for the institution to follow

00:08:14.900 --> 00:08:17.400
[Amit Varma]: or is it part of convention and it's just evolved this way?

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:20.400
[Guest]: So, interestingly, to go back a little bit into history,

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:23.900
[Guest]: India got its laws codified much before Britain did.

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:26.900
[Guest]: Even though we were being ruled by the British same people,

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:29.900
[Guest]: they figured, no, no, no, these people can't be trusted to evolve

00:08:30.400 --> 00:08:31.900
[Guest]: our conventions or understand our traditions.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:32.900
[Guest]: We'll codify everything.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:35.900
[Guest]: The problem is that since then, we haven't moved on.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:36.900
[Guest]: We are still stuck.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:39.900
[Guest]: So, and this is something that I'd like to tell everybody and shocks people.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:43.900
[Guest]: Our Code of Criminal Procedure provides you better civil rights guarantees

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:45.900
[Guest]: than the Constitution of India.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:50.400
[Guest]: If, if, if a judge just followed the Code of Criminal Procedure, right,

00:08:50.900 --> 00:08:52.400
[Guest]: you would ensure that you are heard properly.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:54.400
[Guest]: You would ensure that you are not detained for longer than necessary.

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:56.400
[Guest]: You would ensure that you get a lawyer.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:08:57.400
[Guest]: You would have the right to cross exemption.

00:08:57.900 --> 00:08:59.400
[Guest]: All of this is guaranteed in the Code of Criminal Procedure,

00:08:59.900 --> 00:09:00.400
[Guest]: not our Constitution.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:04.400
[Guest]: Nobody thought that, guys, this is a, you know, a colonial thing.

00:09:04.900 --> 00:09:07.400
[Guest]: Maybe we need to either a change our Code of Criminal Procedure,

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:09.400
[Guest]: that keeping all those civil rights requirements,

00:09:09.900 --> 00:09:12.400
[Guest]: but ensuring that a trial happens quickly or, you know,

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:15.900
[Guest]: we put it into the Constitution to ensure that everything,

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:17.900
[Guest]: other changes can be made more organically as things go on.

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:21.900
[Guest]: So we are now left with a situation where, unfortunately,

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:25.900
[Guest]: all state governments seem to think that the way to ensure quick justice

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:27.900
[Guest]: is to loosen the requirements of the Criminal Justice,

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:30.900
[Guest]: Criminal Procedure Code, which means you won't get bail,

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:32.900
[Guest]: you won't be heard, summary trial.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:35.900
[Guest]: I mean, all this kind of stuff is a basic violation of civil rights

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:39.900
[Guest]: and none of this actually helps in moving a case forward.

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:40.900
[Guest]: All it does.

00:09:40.900 --> 00:09:43.400
[Guest]: So you will find special courts have failed across the country.

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:45.400
[Guest]: Why? Because they will not give proper hearings.

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:47.400
[Guest]: They will pass rush judgments.

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:49.400
[Guest]: And the moment a judge in an appeals court sees it,

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:50.400
[Guest]: they'll say, this is rubbish.

00:09:50.900 --> 00:09:53.400
[Guest]: How can I, how can you possibly convict on so little evidence?

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:54.400
[Amit Varma]: Give me a historical sense of this.

00:09:54.900 --> 00:09:57.400
[Amit Varma]: So when you talk about special courts, what are these special courts?

00:09:57.900 --> 00:09:59.400
[Amit Varma]: What were they set up for? And so on.

00:09:59.900 --> 00:10:03.400
[Guest]: So initially the idea for special courts comes in the fifties.

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:06.400
[Guest]: And the fact that, you know, you feel like, okay,

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:09.400
[Guest]: there are certain crimes in the context of partitions, basically.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:12.900
[Guest]: And, uh, you know, uh, communist, uh, uprisings and so on.

00:10:13.400 --> 00:10:15.900
[Guest]: You want special courts to try certain categories of offenses.

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:19.900
[Guest]: Now, uh, unfortunately the Supreme Court sort of made a mistake by saying,

00:10:20.400 --> 00:10:21.900
[Guest]: okay, find an exceptional situation.

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:23.900
[Guest]: But that exception has widened over the years, right?

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:25.900
[Guest]: In the very, one of the very first cases regarding article 14,

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:27.900
[Guest]: the Supreme Court said in certain exceptional cases,

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:29.900
[Guest]: we'll allow the special courts and so on.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:33.900
[Guest]: But the, nowadays a special court has lost all meaning.

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:36.900
[Guest]: It's your regular court, your regular court that sits in, say, the city.

00:10:36.900 --> 00:10:39.400
[Amit Varma]: But does it have like speed in the procedures or something?

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:41.400
[Guest]: They mess it up, mess around a little bit with it.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:43.400
[Guest]: They don't speed it up as much, so much as to say, okay,

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:44.400
[Guest]: you lose your right to this.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:48.400
[Guest]: You lose your right to cross-examine or you lose your right to apply for bail

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:50.400
[Guest]: or you'll have to do it in three months and so on.

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:52.400
[Guest]: Or what they do, which is even worse,

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:55.400
[Guest]: is to say these categories of offenses will go before the special courts

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:58.400
[Guest]: that the regular procedure is followed and you'll realize it moves quickly.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:01.400
[Guest]: But then that means every other category of cases stuck.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:05.400
[Guest]: So in that way, what causes the problem is that

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:07.900
[Guest]: you're not really resolving the system's issues.

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:09.900
[Guest]: You are addressing one particular part of it,

00:11:10.400 --> 00:11:11.900
[Guest]: but causing 10 other problems, you know,

00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:13.900
[Guest]: like literally you're trying to solve the seen problem

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:15.900
[Guest]: and causing 10 other unseen problems.

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:18.900
[Amit Varma]: Unseen problems, which is a question of capacity,

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:19.900
[Amit Varma]: but we'll get to that later.

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:23.900
[Amit Varma]: So would you say that some of the civil rights protections

00:11:24.400 --> 00:11:27.900
[Amit Varma]: that the criminal code offered, which the constitution doesn't,

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:30.900
[Amit Varma]: are now slowly being taken away by states

00:11:31.400 --> 00:11:32.900
[Amit Varma]: and the constitution doesn't protect them anyway.

00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:33.900
[Amit Varma]: So here we are in trouble.

00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:38.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes. And it's the constitution's job really to have embodied those in the wrong.

00:11:38.900 --> 00:11:42.400
[Guest]: To an extent, yes, because there's a little bit of complacency.

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.400
[Guest]: If you see the constitution, constituent assembly debates,

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:46.400
[Guest]: you know, somebody says, you know,

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:49.400
[Guest]: you should, you should put the right to cross examine in the constitution itself.

00:11:49.900 --> 00:11:51.400
[Guest]: You should put these three, four other things.

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:53.400
[Guest]: Ambedkar sort of dismisses it saying, no, no,

00:11:53.900 --> 00:11:55.400
[Guest]: only a very insane state government will say,

00:11:55.900 --> 00:11:57.400
[Guest]: we'll take away the right to cross examination.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:11:59.400
[Guest]: But consider things like the Gunda's Act, right?

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:01.400
[Guest]: See what procedures they have. There's none.

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:02.400
[Guest]: There's literally none.

00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:03.900
[Guest]: Explain that to me. What is the Gunda's Act?

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:04.900
[Guest]: So for instance,

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.900
[Guest]: the Gunda's Act is to sort of catch hold of people who are quote unquote history

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:09.900
[Guest]: cheaters, those who repeat offenses.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:11.900
[Guest]: It allows the detention, prevent the detention of people.

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:13.900
[Guest]: And there are very little criminal,

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:15.900
[Guest]: like it's one of those where the focus is on,

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:17.900
[Guest]: let's try and get a conviction somehow or the other.

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:19.900
[Guest]: The other egregious thing is the NDPS Act,

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:21.900
[Guest]: Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances Act,

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:24.900
[Guest]: which sort of makes it difficult for you to get bail.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:27.900
[Guest]: There are a whole range of laws that make it difficult for you to get bail.

00:12:28.400 --> 00:12:30.900
[Guest]: Uttar Pradesh has done away with anticipatory bail, right?

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:34.400
[Guest]: In terms of the fact that you're making it as hard as possible

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:36.400
[Guest]: for somebody to get out of jail, you know,

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:38.400
[Guest]: even if they have not actually committed the crime or

00:12:38.900 --> 00:12:41.400
[Guest]: when the Supreme Court has repeatedly tried to say that

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:43.400
[Guest]: bail should be the rule and jail the exception.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:46.400
[Guest]: Now they're trying to change our laws to make it the other way around.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:50.400
[Guest]: And you have other egregious laws like,

00:12:50.900 --> 00:12:52.400
[Guest]: you know, apart from national security,

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:55.400
[Guest]: you also have the Makoka and the UP,

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:58.400
[Guest]: other versions of the Makoka perusing up around the country,

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:01.900
[Guest]: all of which sort of say that confessions obtained

00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:03.900
[Guest]: by a police officer are admissible in court,

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:05.900
[Guest]: you know, which is basically like an incentive to torture,

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:08.900
[Guest]: saying stuff like, you know,

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:10.900
[Guest]: even if we'll loosen the rules of evidence

00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:12.900
[Guest]: so that we don't impose a rigorous standard

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:15.900
[Guest]: to prove that you actually collected this from this person.

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:18.900
[Guest]: So there are a whole range of such sort of

00:13:19.400 --> 00:13:21.900
[Guest]: civil rights weakening happening at the state level

00:13:22.400 --> 00:13:24.900
[Guest]: where they're responding to, oh no, why aren't criminals getting convicted?

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:26.900
[Guest]: The problem is the procedure, not the institution.

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:29.400
[Guest]: So therefore the civil rights are being weakened as a result.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:31.400
[Amit Varma]: So when state governments weaken these civil rights

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:33.400
[Amit Varma]: in these various different ways,

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:35.400
[Amit Varma]: what are the sort of incentives that are playing on them?

00:13:35.900 --> 00:13:37.400
[Amit Varma]: Like, for example, do they want cases to get over quickly?

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Do they want to strengthen their own hands

00:13:39.900 --> 00:13:41.400
[Amit Varma]: so they can do what they want?

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:43.400
[Amit Varma]: What are the incentives playing out here?

00:13:43.900 --> 00:13:46.400
[Guest]: Primarily it is to respond to this public outcry, right?

00:13:46.900 --> 00:13:47.400
[Guest]: So for instance,

00:13:47.900 --> 00:13:49.400
[Amit Varma]: So it's optics, that hey, we are doing something,

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:50.400
[Amit Varma]: strong arm of the law.

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes, A is optics.

00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:54.400
[Guest]: We'll introduce the Gundas Act,

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:55.400
[Guest]: we'll use the NSA,

00:13:55.400 --> 00:13:58.900
[Guest]: we'll use the amendments to the IPC and whatever.

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:00.900
[Guest]: That's the optics.

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:01.900
[Guest]: The second is,

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:03.900
[Guest]: so when the clamour dies down,

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:04.900
[Guest]: they're still left with the power.

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:06.900
[Guest]: So they'll use it as they see fit.

00:14:07.400 --> 00:14:11.900
[Guest]: So they'll use the NSA to jail Chandrasekhar Ravan in Uttar Pradesh

00:14:12.400 --> 00:14:13.900
[Guest]: because he is organizing Dalits.

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:16.900
[Guest]: Or you will use sedition against Hardik Patel in Gujarat

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:18.900
[Guest]: because he's threatening political power.

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:20.900
[Guest]: So when the optics died down,

00:14:21.400 --> 00:14:22.900
[Guest]: the power is still there.

00:14:22.900 --> 00:14:25.400
[Guest]: So which is why, which is why I think,

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:27.400
[Guest]: you know, nobody's going to,

00:14:27.900 --> 00:14:29.400
[Guest]: people aren't framing the problem correctly.

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:32.400
[Guest]: Nobody's saying, hey, let's reform the judiciary.

00:14:32.900 --> 00:14:35.400
[Guest]: If you ask me the reason why we have a criminals in politics problem

00:14:35.900 --> 00:14:38.400
[Guest]: is because the judiciary is not able to decide cases quickly enough against them.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:41.400
[Guest]: If you ask me why people are so outraged about 498A,

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:44.400
[Guest]: it's because we're not actually reforming the judiciary

00:14:44.900 --> 00:14:45.400
[Guest]: so that, you know, obviously,

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:47.400
[Guest]: malafide cases are not being dismissed.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:48.400
[Guest]: That you're not saying,

00:14:48.900 --> 00:14:49.400
[Guest]: why are you arresting this person?

00:14:49.900 --> 00:14:50.400
[Guest]: Right?

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:51.400
[Guest]: Under the code of criminal procedure,

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:52.900
[Guest]: arrest is not something that automatically happens

00:14:53.400 --> 00:14:54.900
[Guest]: just because somebody files an FIR against you.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:56.900
[Guest]: You're not enforcing it against them.

00:14:57.400 --> 00:14:59.900
[Guest]: Even 66A for that matter of the Information Technology Act

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:02.900
[Guest]: was a case where you did not seriously see

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:06.900
[Guest]: you're putting this law in the hands of your local constable.

00:15:07.400 --> 00:15:07.900
[Guest]: Right?

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:09.900
[Guest]: That person is not going to care what,

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:11.900
[Guest]: you know, the fine words of this law mean.

00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:13.900
[Guest]: And he's not going to pull out a dictionary to see

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:15.900
[Amit Varma]: what malicious means or what any of that means.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:16.900
[Amit Varma]: It's a blunt instrument he's going to use.

00:15:17.400 --> 00:15:17.900
[Guest]: It's a blunt instrument.

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:19.900
[Guest]: And even for that blunt instrument,

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:21.400
[Guest]: the court should be able to rectify these things,

00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:22.400
[Guest]: but they're not.

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:23.400
[Guest]: Right?

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:24.400
[Guest]: You file something,

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:26.400
[Guest]: you hope quickly that you'll get a hearing,

00:15:26.900 --> 00:15:29.400
[Guest]: that the prosecutor turns up on time

00:15:29.900 --> 00:15:30.400
[Guest]: and that, you know,

00:15:30.900 --> 00:15:32.400
[Guest]: they will not try and mess up something else.

00:15:32.900 --> 00:15:34.400
[Guest]: People don't have that faith in the judiciary

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:35.400
[Guest]: that if,

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:36.400
[Guest]: even if we have a law,

00:15:36.900 --> 00:15:38.400
[Guest]: which is somewhat egregious,

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:40.400
[Guest]: that there is somebody who can ensure that

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:41.400
[Guest]: things are remedied quickly enough.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:43.400
[Guest]: So which is where the response is

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:44.400
[Guest]: do something about the law itself.

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:45.400
[Guest]: Right?

00:15:45.900 --> 00:15:46.400
[Amit Varma]: Which is completely the wrong response,

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:47.400
[Amit Varma]: which causes more issues.

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:48.400
[Amit Varma]: So let me try and sum up

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:49.900
[Amit Varma]: the two broad problems as I see them

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:50.900
[Amit Varma]: that you pointed out with the judiciary.

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:51.900
[Amit Varma]: So A,

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:52.900
[Amit Varma]: tell me if I'm articulating this properly

00:15:53.400 --> 00:15:53.900
[Amit Varma]: and summing it up properly

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:54.900
[Amit Varma]: and B,

00:15:55.400 --> 00:15:55.900
[Amit Varma]: tell me if you want to add to it.

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:56.900
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

00:15:57.400 --> 00:15:57.900
[Amit Varma]: Problem number one is that

00:15:58.400 --> 00:15:58.900
[Amit Varma]: we have a bloated system

00:15:59.400 --> 00:15:59.900
[Amit Varma]: which doesn't deliver justice

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:00.900
[Amit Varma]: or delays it so inordinately

00:16:01.400 --> 00:16:01.900
[Amit Varma]: that it might as well be called

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:03.900
[Amit Varma]: a denial of justice itself.

00:16:04.400 --> 00:16:04.900
[Amit Varma]: And the reason for that

00:16:05.400 --> 00:16:06.900
[Amit Varma]: is a 19th century mindset

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:08.900
[Amit Varma]: which focuses just on judges giving outcome

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:10.900
[Amit Varma]: and not the speediness of the process.

00:16:11.400 --> 00:16:12.900
[Amit Varma]: And that needs to change.

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:13.900
[Amit Varma]: Problem number two is that

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:14.900
[Amit Varma]: we have a civil rights issue

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:16.900
[Amit Varma]: because certain civil rights

00:16:16.900 --> 00:16:18.400
[Amit Varma]: and certain rights are not protected

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:19.400
[Amit Varma]: by the constitution

00:16:19.900 --> 00:16:20.400
[Amit Varma]: as they should be

00:16:20.900 --> 00:16:21.400
[Amit Varma]: and therefore

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:23.400
[Amit Varma]: they are left at the discretion

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:24.400
[Amit Varma]: of state governments

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:25.400
[Amit Varma]: to tamper with

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:26.400
[Amit Varma]: as and when they feel like

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:27.400
[Amit Varma]: which they often do

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:28.400
[Amit Varma]: for reasons of optics

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:29.400
[Amit Varma]: to show that

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:30.400
[Amit Varma]: hey we are doing something

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:31.400
[Unknown]: about this problem

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:32.400
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:33.400
[Amit Varma]: they may not intend that

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:34.400
[Amit Varma]: but mistakes happen

00:16:34.900 --> 00:16:35.400
[Amit Varma]: because they are not

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:36.400
[Amit Varma]: farsighted enough.

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:37.400
[Amit Varma]: Is that a correct summation?

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:38.400
[Guest]: Yeah,

00:16:38.900 --> 00:16:39.400
[Guest]: that's the correct thing

00:16:39.900 --> 00:16:40.400
[Guest]: and one feeds into the other.

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:41.400
[Guest]: Right?

00:16:41.900 --> 00:16:42.400
[Guest]: One feeds into the other.

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:43.400
[Guest]: You see that

00:16:43.900 --> 00:16:44.400
[Guest]: the fact that our judiciary

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:45.400
[Guest]: is so inefficient

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:46.900
[Guest]: is so unable to deliver

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:47.900
[Guest]: his judgments on time

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:48.900
[Guest]: and ensure a trial

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:49.900
[Guest]: is completed

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:50.900
[Guest]: sort of means that

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:51.900
[Guest]: the thing is

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:52.900
[Guest]: okay we can only do this.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:53.900
[Guest]: Right?

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:54.900
[Guest]: We can only change the law

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:55.900
[Guest]: and if that means

00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:56.900
[Guest]: you'll have to give up

00:16:57.400 --> 00:16:57.900
[Guest]: your civil liberties.

00:16:58.400 --> 00:16:58.900
[Guest]: That's the unfortunate situation

00:16:59.400 --> 00:16:59.900
[Guest]: that we're finding ourselves in.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:00.900
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:01.900
[Amit Varma]: So what are the sort of

00:17:02.400 --> 00:17:02.900
[Amit Varma]: solutions which are

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:03.900
[Amit Varma]: a. typically touted

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:04.900
[Amit Varma]: and b. which you feel

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:05.900
[Amit Varma]: can work?

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:06.900
[Guest]: So

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:07.900
[Guest]: a lot of the times

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:08.900
[Guest]: the solution

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:09.900
[Guest]: that is touted

00:17:10.400 --> 00:17:10.900
[Guest]: is we need more judges.

00:17:11.400 --> 00:17:11.900
[Guest]: That's not true.

00:17:12.400 --> 00:17:12.900
[Guest]: Yes,

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:13.900
[Guest]: of course,

00:17:13.900 --> 00:17:14.900
[Guest]: because Karnataka and

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:15.400
[Guest]: Calcutta High Court

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:16.400
[Guest]: for instance are

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:17.400
[Guest]: recently suffering the

00:17:17.900 --> 00:17:18.400
[Guest]: problem of even a

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:19.400
[Guest]: minimum number of judges

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:20.400
[Guest]: are not being available

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:21.400
[Guest]: just to be able to

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:22.400
[Guest]: handle the existing

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:23.400
[Guest]: case sort of cases.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:24.400
[Guest]: But I think

00:17:24.900 --> 00:17:25.400
[Guest]: the

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:26.400
[Guest]: capacity problem

00:17:26.900 --> 00:17:27.400
[Guest]: in terms of the

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:28.400
[Guest]: number of judges

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:29.400
[Guest]: is somewhat overstated.

00:17:29.900 --> 00:17:30.400
[Guest]: We don't need

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:31.400
[Guest]: that many more.

00:17:31.900 --> 00:17:32.400
[Guest]: Maybe we need about

00:17:32.900 --> 00:17:33.400
[Guest]: 10 or 15 percent

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:34.400
[Amit Varma]: increase in judges

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:35.400
[Amit Varma]: and we'll be fine.

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:36.400
[Amit Varma]: Which is easily doable.

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:37.400
[Amit Varma]: Which is easily doable.

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:38.400
[Guest]: Right.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:39.400
[Guest]: But

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:40.400
[Guest]: to be fair,

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:41.400
[Guest]: I'm going to break

00:17:41.900 --> 00:17:42.400
[Guest]: that on a little bit

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:43.400
[Guest]: for you, which is

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:43.900
[Guest]: reasonably easily

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:44.900
[Guest]: doable.

00:17:45.400 --> 00:17:45.900
[Guest]: So

00:17:46.400 --> 00:17:46.900
[Guest]: capacity is not

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:47.900
[Guest]: so much of an issue.

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:48.900
[Guest]: Computerization is

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:49.900
[Guest]: touted as

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:50.900
[Guest]: a big

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:51.900
[Guest]: solution to problems.

00:17:52.400 --> 00:17:52.900
[Guest]: But you're talking

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:53.900
[Guest]: about a country

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:54.900
[Guest]: where not all

00:17:55.400 --> 00:17:55.900
[Guest]: trial courts have

00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:56.900
[Guest]: access to

00:17:57.400 --> 00:17:57.900
[Guest]: electricity.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:17:58.900
[Guest]: So what

00:17:59.400 --> 00:17:59.900
[Guest]: computerization

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:00.900
[Guest]: are you talking

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:01.900
[Guest]: about?

00:18:02.400 --> 00:18:02.900
[Guest]: So NCAER did

00:18:03.400 --> 00:18:03.900
[Guest]: this fascinating

00:18:04.400 --> 00:18:04.900
[Guest]: study on how

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:05.900
[Guest]: the e-court

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:06.900
[Guest]: system has

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:07.900
[Guest]: worked in India.

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:08.900
[Guest]: They studied

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:09.900
[Guest]: about five

00:18:10.400 --> 00:18:10.900
[Guest]: states.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:11.900
[Guest]: If you have to file a case

00:18:11.900 --> 00:18:12.400
