00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:02.800
[Guest]: Party here, party here.

00:20:02.800 --> 00:20:03.800
[Guest]: Ready to mediate?

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:04.800
[Guest]: Refer to mediation.

00:20:04.800 --> 00:20:06.720
[Guest]: We had 65 cases done that way.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:09.040
[Guest]: Remaining five cases, we tried mediating, not happening.

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:10.040
[Guest]: Fine.

00:20:10.040 --> 00:20:11.040
[Guest]: I'll fix dates for trial.

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:12.040
[Guest]: We start here.

00:20:12.040 --> 00:20:13.040
[Guest]: We end this date.

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:14.040
[Guest]: We start here.

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:15.040
[Guest]: We end this date.

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:16.040
[Guest]: So again, layman's question.

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:17.040
[Guest]: What do you mean by mediation?

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:18.040
[Guest]: What happens?

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:20.480
[Guest]: So mediation is when you sit down with the mediator, person who knows how to bring parties

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:24.800
[Guest]: to this thing, you arrive at some sort of a consensus that this is how we'll settle

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:25.800
[Guest]: a dispute.

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:26.800
[Amit Varma]: And you need a consensus.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:27.800
[Amit Varma]: So it's not a judgment.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:28.800
[Guest]: It's not a judgment.

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:29.800
[Guest]: Right.

00:20:29.800 --> 00:20:32.200
[Guest]: And the point is that mediators job is to just help you come to a consensus.

00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:34.400
[Guest]: They will not say you guys should resolve it like this.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:35.800
[Guest]: They will not say you guys should do this.

00:20:35.800 --> 00:20:37.880
[Guest]: They'll say, okay, what is the issue?

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:38.880
[Guest]: Why are you here?

00:20:38.880 --> 00:20:41.020
[Guest]: What do you really want from this case?

00:20:41.020 --> 00:20:42.400
[Guest]: What are you willing to let go?

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:46.080
[Guest]: And they have it with both parties individually sitting with parties.

00:20:46.080 --> 00:20:50.060
[Guest]: It's a, I would say labor intensive process because in court, it's easy to say list after

00:20:50.060 --> 00:20:52.160
[Guest]: four weeks, file document, whatever.

00:20:52.160 --> 00:20:56.320
[Guest]: This requires a certain level of empathy, understanding and patience.

00:20:56.320 --> 00:21:01.480
[Guest]: They feel a lot of times it's happened, but a good mediator will be able to ensure that

00:21:01.480 --> 00:21:05.760
[Guest]: parties find the common ground and say, you know what, okay, I'm willing to let go of

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:09.440
[Guest]: a little bit of this because I'm still getting this, or actually all I just wanted was this

00:21:09.440 --> 00:21:11.000
[Amit Varma]: and that person is willing to give me this.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.040
[Amit Varma]: Is it kind of data about like what percentage of cases go to mediation and what percentage

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:16.040
[Guest]: succeed?

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:18.260
[Guest]: So we tried to do that study.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:19.560
[Guest]: We have actually done that study.

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:23.080
[Guest]: So we were able to get the data only from Delhi, Bangalore and Tamil Nadu.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:26.360
[Amit Varma]: By we of course you mean Delhi which is a legal firm.

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:29.160
[Guest]: So we were commissioned by the department of justice to do this study on mediation.

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:30.720
[Guest]: That report is on our website.

00:21:30.720 --> 00:21:35.760
[Guest]: The exact figures I don't have instantly, but a significantly large number now it can

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:37.080
[Guest]: be improved, right?

00:21:37.080 --> 00:21:44.600
[Guest]: Uh, in the sense that if we had more mediators, if more people are aware and if more trained

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:49.320
[Guest]: mediators at the moment, mediators are still doing this as their second job, whereas when

00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:52.160
[Guest]: other countries in the world, it's a full-fledged profession.

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:56.480
[Guest]: People usually are some sort of lawyer or some sort of a retired judge.

00:21:56.480 --> 00:21:59.560
[Guest]: They're happy doing the other things and they mediate because they offer their services

00:21:59.560 --> 00:22:03.120
[Guest]: for free for the, there's a Bangalore mediation center, there's a mediation center at the

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:04.120
[Guest]: Delhi high court.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:08.320
[Guest]: They work as well as they do within their constraints, but it could be a hundred X better

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:11.680
[Guest]: if you ask me with sufficient funding and training and some interest put into it, it

00:22:11.680 --> 00:22:14.080
[Guest]: will be a hundred X better.

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:15.080
[Guest]: Arbitration.

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:19.400
[Guest]: Um, in our arbitration is basically like a court setting, but outside the court you do

00:22:19.400 --> 00:22:20.400
[Guest]: it.

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:23.600
[Guest]: It's a private court, you know, then in a way manner of speaking, unfortunately in our

00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:26.640
[Guest]: country, uh, arbitration is dominated by retired judges.

00:22:26.640 --> 00:22:28.800
[Guest]: So they bring that particular approach to them.

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:33.280
[Guest]: Uh, so they're also insistent on following certain rules and unfortunately our courts

00:22:33.280 --> 00:22:36.640
[Guest]: are not very helpful when it comes to handling arbitration questions.

00:22:36.640 --> 00:22:40.840
[Guest]: But if you have a good professional network of arbitrators, if you have good institutions

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:45.600
[Guest]: which facilitate arbitration, you can, all, most of the high value disputes which come

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:47.600
[Amit Varma]: to court will immediately get moved over there.

00:22:47.600 --> 00:22:48.600
[Amit Varma]: And again, so what exactly is arbitration?

00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:51.920
[Amit Varma]: So it's like if you and I have a dispute, we go to court and they tell us, Hey, why

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:53.840
[Amit Varma]: don't we go for arbitration and we go for arbitration.

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:54.840
[Guest]: Is the decision binding?

00:22:54.840 --> 00:22:55.840
[Guest]: Yes, it is.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:56.840
[Amit Varma]: It is binding.

00:22:56.840 --> 00:23:00.840
[Amit Varma]: If we agree to go for arbitration, the decision is binding, but it's guaranteed to happen

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:02.080
[Guest]: within a certain amount of time.

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:05.760
[Guest]: So that is how the law should be, right?

00:23:05.760 --> 00:23:08.800
[Guest]: And they've amended the law to try and make it, that would then be the incentive.

00:23:08.800 --> 00:23:09.800
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:23:09.800 --> 00:23:10.800
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:23:10.800 --> 00:23:14.120
[Guest]: Now the advantage for me is I'm not dependent on 60 other cases being heard before my arbitration

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:15.120
[Guest]: is heard.

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:17.840
[Guest]: I am not dependent on the judge have not being on leave and so on.

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:19.720
[Guest]: We fix the dates at our convenience.

00:23:19.720 --> 00:23:22.160
[Guest]: We figure out what's convenient for the arbitrator and us.

00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:25.620
[Guest]: And a primary reason for a lot of arbitration is confidentiality.

00:23:25.620 --> 00:23:29.740
[Guest]: You don't have to make the documents public if it is a say commercial issue.

00:23:29.740 --> 00:23:31.800
[Guest]: So in that sense, that is what arbitration does.

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:35.440
[Guest]: It's essentially like a private court, but it is, it's orders will be enforced as if

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:36.440
[Guest]: it's the orders of a court.

00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:39.040
[Guest]: You don't need to go to court again and say, make this the final decree.

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:40.040
[Guest]: And they'll say, yeah, done.

00:23:40.040 --> 00:23:41.040
[Guest]: You have to follow it.

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:44.440
[Guest]: If there's any difficulty in following it, we'll smoothen the process.

00:23:44.440 --> 00:23:49.840
[Guest]: So, but the problem is in India, most of the arbitrations are what are called ad hoc arbitrations,

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:54.160
[Guest]: which means you and I agree to arbitrate, there's a dispute, and then we go looking

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:55.640
[Guest]: for who will be the arbitrator.

00:23:55.640 --> 00:23:59.560
[Guest]: Whereas the practice should be that we, you and I will agree that, Hey, there's this institution

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:01.640
[Guest]: which does arbitration.

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:02.920
[Guest]: They will select the arbitrator.

00:24:02.920 --> 00:24:03.920
[Guest]: They have a certain set of rules.

00:24:03.920 --> 00:24:07.320
[Guest]: They, they will guarantee that it will be done in one year, but we will go looking for

00:24:07.320 --> 00:24:10.600
[Guest]: an arbitrator, somebody who, you know, both of us can figure out, we'll do this quickly

00:24:10.600 --> 00:24:14.160
[Guest]: and we'll provide us with this thing, provided you and I are both on the same page that we

00:24:14.160 --> 00:24:15.640
[Guest]: want this dispute to be resolved.

00:24:15.640 --> 00:24:16.640
[Guest]: Right?

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:17.640
[Guest]: Right.

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:19.680
[Amit Varma]: Supposing I want this delayed and you want this done quickly, then we can find ways to

00:24:19.680 --> 00:24:22.280
[Amit Varma]: stay in court for a hundred years, a hundred years.

00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:26.400
[Guest]: But I'm assuming the time that parties wanted, this arbitration is an option.

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:29.400
[Guest]: And there are other things like conciliation and there are negotiations.

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:33.660
[Guest]: These are all mechanisms which our laws provide for, but no effort has been put into making

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:37.200
[Guest]: them effective alternates to litigation.

00:24:37.200 --> 00:24:41.680
[Amit Varma]: But these are also sort of, they strike me as solutions that treat the symptoms while

00:24:41.680 --> 00:24:46.120
[Amit Varma]: the, you know, the root cause of the disease, like you described the 19th century mindset

00:24:46.120 --> 00:24:50.560
[Amit Varma]: and the conventions and rules around the judiciary process.

00:24:50.560 --> 00:24:51.740
[Guest]: These don't address those.

00:24:51.740 --> 00:24:56.920
[Guest]: So they don't, but it has to be, if you see the judiciary as one element of a dispute

00:24:56.920 --> 00:25:00.880
[Guest]: resolution process, right, you will realize, Oh, hang on, what's the big deal in having

00:25:00.880 --> 00:25:03.520
[Guest]: people file suits for everything, right?

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:06.340
[Guest]: They can go sort this out through mediation, conciliation and arbitration.

00:25:06.340 --> 00:25:10.880
[Guest]: And if it is something you absolutely cannot resolve, then we get to the next stage.

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:15.640
[Guest]: And then the next stage is what, say something like the commercial courts act in India tries

00:25:15.640 --> 00:25:16.640
[Guest]: to do.

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:17.640
[Guest]: Right.

00:25:17.640 --> 00:25:20.320
[Guest]: So I was part of the drafting process, the law commission of India, and there was an

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:21.840
[Guest]: existing draft, which was terrible.

00:25:21.840 --> 00:25:24.400
[Guest]: And we figured, okay, that's, that's, there's no way that this can become the law.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:28.680
[Guest]: And when we looked around the world, we studied how the philosophical approach to litigation

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:30.400
[Guest]: to a case has changed around the world.

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:34.760
[Guest]: And we found that more countries in the world put the judge at the center of the case.

00:25:34.760 --> 00:25:35.760
[Guest]: Okay.

00:25:35.760 --> 00:25:38.400
[Guest]: Now that you've decided, I need this to be decided by a judge, fine, you're going to

00:25:38.400 --> 00:25:39.400
[Guest]: follow his orders.

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:40.720
[Guest]: You're going to follow his rules.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:43.880
[Guest]: The judge will now say, okay, you have three months, complete all the documents, whatever

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:44.880
[Guest]: you want to file.

00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:48.040
[Guest]: Uh, you have one week, finish everything that you need to in this one week.

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:49.040
[Guest]: All right.

00:25:49.040 --> 00:25:50.560
[Amit Varma]: And you have at least five days for hearing evidence.

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:54.680
[Amit Varma]: And does it, do those judges have rule based guidelines which tell them that this is a

00:25:54.680 --> 00:25:56.160
[Guest]: process within this much time?

00:25:56.160 --> 00:25:57.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:25:57.160 --> 00:25:58.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:25:58.160 --> 00:25:59.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:25:59.160 --> 00:26:00.160
[Guest]: Yes.

00:26:00.160 --> 00:26:01.960
[Guest]: So we have also in that particular law, we have also amended the code of civil procedure

00:26:01.960 --> 00:26:05.880
[Guest]: to try and update a little bit to say that, okay, now the judge will have the powers to

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:09.920
[Guest]: say in four weeks to this, in eight weeks to this, in 12 weeks to this, and giving them

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:11.620
[Guest]: no discretion to extend the time.

00:26:11.620 --> 00:26:15.160
[Guest]: Because what happened to the previous attempt at amending the CPC was everything became

00:26:15.160 --> 00:26:16.160
[Guest]: discretionary.

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:17.160
[Guest]: Right.

00:26:17.160 --> 00:26:21.560
[Guest]: So, um, the, and so far the way this law has been interpreted, courts are consistently

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:25.720
[Guest]: saying this is a law made to cut down time fully taken for litigation.

00:26:25.720 --> 00:26:27.520
[Amit Varma]: So we're not going to give anybody second chances.

00:26:27.520 --> 00:26:31.000
[Guest]: So this applies to what commercial cases, commercial cases above a value of one crore.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Okay.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.000
[Guest]: So we're just high value commercial business.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:35.960
[Guest]: They usually take a long time to dispose of because you'll find mountains and mountains

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:36.960
[Amit Varma]: of papers.

00:26:36.960 --> 00:26:39.720
[Guest]: Parties can lengthen it as long as they want to.

00:26:39.720 --> 00:26:43.240
[Guest]: So the idea of this law is to cut it short to say that, look, just tell us what are the

00:26:43.240 --> 00:26:45.680
[Guest]: five points you're discussing, you're disputing, right?

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:47.200
[Amit Varma]: Tell us who will be the people who will come.

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:48.200
[Amit Varma]: So is it then mandatory?

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:51.320
[Amit Varma]: Like if we have a dispute, which is more than that amount, is it mandatory for us to go

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:52.320
[Amit Varma]: to?

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:53.320
[Guest]: So it depends.

00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:54.320
[Guest]: Jurisdiction, jurisdiction.

00:26:54.320 --> 00:26:56.400
[Guest]: So we have left it to the discretion of the state government because they'll know how

00:26:56.400 --> 00:26:57.400
[Guest]: many such cases are there.

00:26:57.400 --> 00:26:58.400
[Guest]: But they can make it mandatory.

00:26:58.400 --> 00:26:59.400
[Amit Varma]: They can.

00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:00.400
[Amit Varma]: So it is mandatory.

00:27:00.400 --> 00:27:01.400
[Guest]: So all cases are normally transferred.

00:27:01.400 --> 00:27:04.040
[Guest]: So it started with the Bombay High Court and the Delhi High Court, where usually a one

00:27:04.040 --> 00:27:06.080
[Guest]: crore plus cases used to be filed.

00:27:06.080 --> 00:27:11.760
[Guest]: So the high court set up a commercial court and a commercial, a commercial division and

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:13.320
[Guest]: a commercial appellate division.

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:15.080
[Guest]: So all the cases were transferred there.

00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:17.760
[Guest]: Now we're seeing more and more state government setting up commercial courts.

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:22.200
[Guest]: Um, the, the, the decision is not that much as to do a little bit with India's judicial

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:23.200
[Guest]: history.

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:24.200
[Guest]: I'll come to that in a little bit.

00:27:24.200 --> 00:27:27.000
[Guest]: So for instance, Karnataka just set up a commercial court, Rajasthan has set up a commercial court,

00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.520
[Guest]: uh, UP is in the process of setting up a commercial court and other and Chhattisgarh has set up

00:27:30.520 --> 00:27:31.520
[Guest]: a commercial court.

00:27:31.520 --> 00:27:34.160
[Guest]: So they're saying that, okay, this seems to work.

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:36.440
[Guest]: Investors are saying cases are moving quickly.

00:27:36.440 --> 00:27:41.360
[Guest]: We're not getting stuck in this litigation and uh, maybe it may be a good idea for you

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:42.360
[Guest]: to also set it up.

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:46.080
[Guest]: So it's, uh, and they're also being assessed by the government on, are you setting up a

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:47.080
[Guest]: commercial court?

00:27:47.080 --> 00:27:48.320
[Guest]: Which it's easy enough.

00:27:48.320 --> 00:27:51.840
[Guest]: The only thing is how well they train the judges, get the right judges, how well they

00:27:51.840 --> 00:27:52.840
[Guest]: coordinate the high court.

00:27:52.840 --> 00:27:56.360
[Guest]: So we'll see over the few years, but this is the first attempt, I think, at really trying

00:27:56.360 --> 00:27:59.040
[Guest]: to change the mindset of how our courts should be like.

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic.

00:28:00.040 --> 00:28:04.400
[Amit Varma]: And now your argument also, therefore would be that if we, you know, we are trying to

00:28:04.400 --> 00:28:08.760
[Amit Varma]: change the rules of the game so that this mindset dominates and delivers justice faster

00:28:08.760 --> 00:28:11.960
[Amit Varma]: and therefore fairer at these commercial courts.

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:13.680
[Guest]: Why should that not apply to all courts?

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:14.680
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:28:14.680 --> 00:28:15.680
[Guest]: It should.

00:28:15.680 --> 00:28:16.680
[Guest]: But I think it'll take time.

00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:21.160
[Guest]: The reason why I said it'll take time is that our profession, the legal profession, when

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:26.880
[Guest]: I say our profession, I mean the legal profession, um, in India is extremely skewed.

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:32.320
[Guest]: Um, you can't expect that somebody who has the capacity to move a case quickly, uh, at

00:28:32.320 --> 00:28:36.680
[Guest]: say for a one crore kind of dispute will be able to do that for like a smaller dispute

00:28:36.680 --> 00:28:39.520
[Guest]: where they're dealing with somebody who was barely paying them any fees.

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:45.320
[Guest]: Um, I sort of wrote about this, I think 7% of lawyers in any court, right?

00:28:45.320 --> 00:28:49.080
[Guest]: And I checked this at the trial court level and the Supreme Court level, 7% of the lawyers

00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:51.680
[Guest]: seem to have 50% of the cases.

00:28:51.680 --> 00:28:52.680
[Guest]: Wow.

00:28:52.680 --> 00:28:56.400
[Guest]: And I'm considering each case to have the same value, but it is not right.

00:28:56.400 --> 00:29:00.360
[Guest]: I'm sure that if I broke it down by the kind of case, how much money was involved, what

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:04.880
[Guest]: fees are being paid, I'm pretty sure that 7% of the lawyers are making about 90% of

00:29:04.880 --> 00:29:05.880
[Guest]: the money.

00:29:05.880 --> 00:29:06.880
[Guest]: Right, right.

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:10.760
[Guest]: So that doesn't mean you ignore the remaining 93% they're handling a large number of cases,

00:29:10.760 --> 00:29:13.800
[Guest]: but they may not have the capacity to move as quickly.

00:29:13.800 --> 00:29:14.800
[Guest]: Right.

00:29:14.800 --> 00:29:19.560
[Guest]: And if you, you don't want to risk imposing a kind of burden on the litigant that they're

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:21.220
[Guest]: not able to match up to you.

00:29:21.220 --> 00:29:25.560
[Guest]: So if you start this as a practice, if people see, ah, this is how it is done.

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:30.760
[Guest]: And you know, maybe sort of adopt those practices or maybe if you find that the legal profession

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:36.280
[Guest]: gets more organized and people are able to do this in a better way, then of course it

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:37.280
[Guest]: can be extended.

00:29:37.280 --> 00:29:40.680
[Amit Varma]: But would you say that then this is a problem with the supply of lawyers in the sense that

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:44.640
[Amit Varma]: you have those lawyers being supplied who can be part of the elite 7% who are making

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:48.800
[Guest]: all the money, but otherwise you have substandard lawyers, not to mean that word in a pejorative

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:49.800
[Guest]: way.

00:29:49.800 --> 00:29:51.040
[Guest]: That's absolutely right.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:54.920
[Guest]: And that's absolutely right because we are seeing the effects of about four decades of

00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:56.320
[Guest]: neglect of legal education.

00:29:56.320 --> 00:30:01.640
[Amit Varma]: So can I then take a detour into that and into talking about legal education and where

00:30:01.640 --> 00:30:04.240
[Amit Varma]: has it gone wrong and what could change that?

00:30:04.240 --> 00:30:09.000
[Guest]: So initially the law colleges were all set up by government, the GLC in Bombay and GLC

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.600
[Guest]: here, university law college here, you find GLC everywhere.

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:17.520
[Guest]: Governments did put a bit into investing in law colleges and they did produce excellent

00:30:17.520 --> 00:30:23.480
[Guest]: lawyers but post independence, um, not to sound like I'm the guy blaming Nehru, but

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:24.840
[Guest]: somehow the nation sort of got obsessed.

00:30:24.840 --> 00:30:28.040
[Guest]: We need more engineers and doctors and lawyers will come on their own.

00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:29.040
[Guest]: What is that?

00:30:29.040 --> 00:30:33.680
[Guest]: Uh, so it meant that most of the legal education now was taken over the private sector.

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:38.160
[Guest]: It was a kind of de facto privatization if I want to call it where law colleges could

00:30:38.160 --> 00:30:39.160
[Guest]: be open.

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:42.520
[Guest]: So now you now have the bar council of India which says, okay, fine, this law college meets

00:30:42.520 --> 00:30:43.520
[Guest]: our requirements.

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:45.120
[Guest]: So you're allowed to open and function.

00:30:45.120 --> 00:30:49.480
[Amit Varma]: And uh, the bar council would control the supply, like they would, they would be doing

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:50.480
[Guest]: licensing and stuff like that.

00:30:50.480 --> 00:30:51.480
[Guest]: Yes, yes, yes.

00:30:51.480 --> 00:30:52.480
[Guest]: They would.

00:30:52.480 --> 00:30:55.720
[Unknown]: I mean the control is exercised very loosely in a manner of speaking, there was literally

00:30:55.720 --> 00:30:56.720
[Unknown]: no control.

00:30:56.720 --> 00:30:59.720
[Guest]: There was like, fine, if you want to set up your setup, as long as you pay us the fat

00:30:59.720 --> 00:31:00.720
[Guest]: price.

00:31:00.720 --> 00:31:02.600
[Guest]: That is basically what it became after a while.

00:31:02.600 --> 00:31:05.720
[Guest]: Sometime in the eighties they realized, oh no, you know, like this time to sort of see

00:31:05.720 --> 00:31:08.800
[Guest]: it, take legal education seriously and which is when we had the national law school set

00:31:08.800 --> 00:31:09.800
[Guest]: up.

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:11.160
[Guest]: They weren't sure will this work, not work.

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:14.440
[Guest]: But when it's been about a decade in and realize, oh wow, you know, we're like actually succeeding

00:31:14.440 --> 00:31:15.440
[Guest]: at this.

00:31:15.440 --> 00:31:16.840
[Guest]: We set up more national law schools.

00:31:16.840 --> 00:31:20.960
[Guest]: Now I think the number is about at about 20 and they're mushrooming.

00:31:20.960 --> 00:31:24.800
[Guest]: A lot of private universities have also sort of seen this as a standard we have to aim

00:31:24.800 --> 00:31:26.480
[Guest]: to, but we don't have to meet them.

00:31:26.480 --> 00:31:29.360
[Guest]: But the fact is that lawyers are in the system.

00:31:29.360 --> 00:31:32.920
[Guest]: The fact is, uh, the law, a law degree was possibly one of the cheapest degrees you could

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:36.520
[Guest]: get, you know, as a professional degrees, right?

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:37.520
[Guest]: Medicine is expensive.

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:38.520
[Guest]: Engineering was expensive.

00:31:38.520 --> 00:31:39.520
[Guest]: Dentistry, whatever.

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:40.520
[Guest]: Everything was expensive.

00:31:40.520 --> 00:31:43.120
[Guest]: But as a professional degree, the law was the cheapest to get.

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:48.680
[Guest]: Um, anybody and everybody could do a law degree and it's great in terms of ensuring the number

00:31:48.680 --> 00:31:49.680
[Guest]: of degrees are there.

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:54.200
[Guest]: But when they actually entered the profession, they realized we're not going to be able to

00:31:54.200 --> 00:31:55.200
[Amit Varma]: make a living.

00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:56.200
[Guest]: Right?

00:31:56.200 --> 00:31:57.200
[Guest]: Right.

00:31:57.200 --> 00:31:58.200
[Guest]: So it's a struggle for the remaining 93%.

00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:02.160
[Guest]: Uh, I think what you're seeing in terms of lawyer strikes, what you're seeing in terms

00:32:02.160 --> 00:32:05.880
[Guest]: of a goondism by lawyers is a reflection of this.

00:32:05.880 --> 00:32:08.520
[Guest]: It's a reflection of the fact that I have invested six years of my life trying to become

00:32:08.520 --> 00:32:09.520
[Guest]: a lawyer.

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:12.120
[Guest]: I have, but now I realize that it's useless.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:13.640
[Guest]: Nothing else I can do now.

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:18.000
[Guest]: And uh, you try to make a living in some way or the other and you find a bad faith ways

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:19.000
[Amit Varma]: of doing so.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:20.000
[Amit Varma]: It's a supply demand mismatch there.

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:21.160
[Guest]: Why is that happening?

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:26.900
[Guest]: Why is that happening is because, so the mismatch happens usually when the, there is no price

00:32:26.900 --> 00:32:28.080
[Guest]: information trickling through.

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:29.080
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:32:29.080 --> 00:32:30.080
[Guest]: Right.

00:32:30.080 --> 00:32:31.080
[Guest]: Right.

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:33.400
[Guest]: Actually, Adam Smith describes this very well and I can do no better than quote him.

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:38.440
[Guest]: Um, even he points us out when he talks about the legal profession in the 18th century England,

00:32:38.440 --> 00:32:41.240
[Guest]: he says that his favorite number seems to be 20.

00:32:41.240 --> 00:32:44.680
[Amit Varma]: So it's not as if he chooses the exact right, he uses 20 all over the place.

00:32:44.680 --> 00:32:49.480
[Guest]: So he says of 20 people, only one lawyer can succeed and he'll make as much as the remaining

00:32:49.480 --> 00:32:50.480
[Amit Varma]: 19.

00:32:50.480 --> 00:32:51.480
[Guest]: Right.

00:32:51.480 --> 00:32:52.480
[Guest]: Right.

00:32:52.480 --> 00:32:56.560
[Guest]: He says that because in the nature of the legal profession as it stands, all 19 believe

00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:58.160
[Amit Varma]: they can be that one person.

00:32:58.160 --> 00:32:59.160
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:00.160
[Amit Varma]: That's a survivorship bias.

00:33:00.160 --> 00:33:01.160
[Amit Varma]: You see the guys who succeed.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.920
[Guest]: You see the guys who succeeded to think I can become that person, but you don't actually

00:33:03.920 --> 00:33:05.240
[Guest]: know what happens to the remaining 90.

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:06.240
[Guest]: So they kind of disappear.

00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:08.040
[Guest]: Um, there is that.

00:33:08.040 --> 00:33:11.800
[Guest]: The second thing also is that the law is a profession where just getting a degree doesn't

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:12.800
[Guest]: help you.

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:16.760
[Guest]: It means you've fulfilled the most basic threshold to be allowed to wear that black coat and

00:33:16.760 --> 00:33:18.040
[Guest]: go into court.

00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:22.000
[Guest]: But to be a successful lawyer, you need about 10 years worth into the profession.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:23.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.240
[Guest]: Um, and he's talking about a situation where you say you don't have the advantage of somebody

00:33:26.240 --> 00:33:27.240
[Guest]: handing over the practice.

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:28.240
[Amit Varma]: You're your father.

00:33:28.240 --> 00:33:29.240
[Amit Varma]: You'll apprentice somewhere.

00:33:29.240 --> 00:33:30.240
[Amit Varma]: You'll clock somewhere.

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:31.440
[Amit Varma]: You'll learn the ropes.

00:33:31.440 --> 00:33:34.880
[Guest]: You try desperately to get clients and hope you survive long enough.

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:39.160
[Guest]: So once you survive, once you cross the 10 year threshold, your peers have all fallen

00:33:39.160 --> 00:33:40.160
[Guest]: off the radar.

00:33:40.160 --> 00:33:42.440
[Guest]: So now you make as much money as 20 of them.

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:43.440
[Guest]: Right.

00:33:43.440 --> 00:33:44.440
[Amit Varma]: That's what happens.

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:45.440
[Amit Varma]: Is this like this across the world?

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:48.680
[Guest]: Like how is it in the U S in the U S it's a much more organized profession.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:53.440
[Guest]: You see in India, 90, I would say about 95 to 99% of lawyers are in solo practitioners

00:33:53.440 --> 00:33:55.480
[Guest]: or maybe no more than two or three.

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:59.600
[Guest]: Whereas around the world, as economies economies develop, the scale of legal services needed

00:33:59.600 --> 00:34:01.760
[Guest]: requires law firms.

00:34:01.760 --> 00:34:05.400
[Guest]: In India, law firms are still becoming bigger and bigger in size.

00:34:05.400 --> 00:34:07.240
[Guest]: Our biggest law firm just split in half.

00:34:07.240 --> 00:34:11.960
[Guest]: So we can't even just say that, uh, you know, uh, that we are getting there.

00:34:11.960 --> 00:34:15.320
[Guest]: Uh, and law firms in India keeps splitting into smaller and smaller sizes.

00:34:15.320 --> 00:34:20.120
[Guest]: Uh, but ideally the services require you, you to have a full fledged law firm.

00:34:20.120 --> 00:34:22.680
[Guest]: Uh, we have not gotten there yet.

00:34:22.680 --> 00:34:24.360
[Guest]: Profession needs to be more organized.

00:34:24.360 --> 00:34:28.560
[Amit Varma]: But do you think this is something we'll evolve towards in India or something needs to be

00:34:28.560 --> 00:34:29.760
[Guest]: done to, uh, provide

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:31.240
[Guest]: We'll evolve towards that.

00:34:31.240 --> 00:34:36.480
[Guest]: But I think to be done, we need to sort of ensure that people understand this is what

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:41.160
[Guest]: getting into the legal profession means that, uh, you're probably going to fail and that

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:42.160
[Guest]: there's no other way to put it.

00:34:42.160 --> 00:34:46.080
[Guest]: Uh, you've got a law degree, uh, congratulations, but you're probably going to fail in the profession.

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:47.080
[Amit Varma]: This is kind of like Bollywood.

00:34:47.080 --> 00:34:50.600
[Amit Varma]: Like I live in Warsaw in Mumbai and I go to the cafes and there are strugglers all around.

00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:55.040
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, everyone is a survivorship bias again, everyone is thinking of the, uh,

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:57.920
[Amit Varma]: Manoj Bajpai or the Nawazuddin Siddiqui or the strugglers who make it.

00:34:57.920 --> 00:34:59.760
[Amit Varma]: They don't see that most strugglers don't make it.

00:34:59.760 --> 00:35:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And I'm really surprised to hear from you that the law is like that because I would

00:35:02.840 --> 00:35:06.280
[Amit Varma]: have thought, you know, as a profession, it would be more like medicine and engineering.

00:35:06.280 --> 00:35:10.160
[Guest]: No, it's not because even medicine, medicine, there are hospitals, right?

00:35:10.160 --> 00:35:15.600
[Guest]: There are hospitals and there's only a small layer of, uh, everybody works within institutions.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:20.440
[Guest]: In the law, unfortunately we don't because the law firm being the default is not there

00:35:20.440 --> 00:35:21.440
[Guest]: for us.

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:23.280
[Guest]: The default is still as a solo practitioner.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:24.280
[Guest]: You set up this thing.

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:28.000
[Guest]: Even our courts, you know, like the way they allocate chambers to lawyers, right?

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:30.560
[Guest]: They're still obsessed with the small solo practitioner.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:35.040
[Guest]: They're not thinking about law firms, the big institution, and even then their filings

00:35:35.040 --> 00:35:36.040
[Amit Varma]: are relatively...

00:35:36.040 --> 00:35:37.040
[Guest]: It's a jolly LLB.

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:38.040
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:35:38.040 --> 00:35:42.080
[Guest]: I think that between the two movies, they pretty much cover most of the pathologies

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:43.080
[Guest]: of the legal system.

00:35:43.080 --> 00:35:46.200
[Guest]: And yes, there's an element of exaggeration, but I think they've nailed it.

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:47.200
[Amit Varma]: They're actually superb films.

00:35:47.200 --> 00:35:50.400
[Amit Varma]: I mean, they're good entertainment, but they're also, you know, they nail a lot of the things.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:51.400
[Guest]: They nail a lot of things.

00:35:51.400 --> 00:35:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:35:52.400 --> 00:35:57.120
[Amit Varma]: So let's move back from legal education to the law itself and a lot of the solutions

00:35:57.120 --> 00:36:02.920
[Amit Varma]: that you kind of discussed take the pressure away by providing alternative ways of arriving

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:06.560
[Amit Varma]: at judgments, whether it's mediation or arbitration or the commercial courts that you pointed

00:36:06.560 --> 00:36:07.560
[Unknown]: out.

00:36:07.560 --> 00:36:12.360
[Amit Varma]: But do you then think that it's simply a matter of finding all these fixes or is there some

00:36:12.360 --> 00:36:16.760
[Amit Varma]: fundamental change required and how hard or easy is that fundamental change to actually

00:36:16.760 --> 00:36:18.640
[Guest]: bring about what is required for it?

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:24.160
[Guest]: So I don't see a fund because all these things put together will create that fundamental

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:25.160
[Amit Varma]: change.

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:26.160
[Guest]: Sure.

00:36:26.160 --> 00:36:27.160
[Guest]: But that 19th century mindset.

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:28.160
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:29.440
[Guest]: So it requires it.

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:35.480
[Guest]: I think the fundamental change is for the top section of the legal profession and judges

00:36:35.480 --> 00:36:36.960
[Guest]: to accept that the system is broken.

00:36:36.960 --> 00:36:37.960
[Guest]: Do they?

00:36:37.960 --> 00:36:38.960
[Guest]: They don't.

00:36:38.960 --> 00:36:39.960
[Guest]: That's the, that's the pity.

00:36:39.960 --> 00:36:41.920
[Guest]: I mean, yes, we saw the press conference.

00:36:41.920 --> 00:36:45.680
[Guest]: That means that's the first inclination that guys, I don't think things are working out

00:36:45.680 --> 00:36:47.220
[Guest]: as they should.

00:36:47.220 --> 00:36:50.840
[Guest]: But there's a sense of complacency at the top rungs of the profession that things are

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:51.840
[Guest]: fine.

00:36:51.840 --> 00:36:52.840
[Guest]: There are problems.

00:36:52.840 --> 00:36:53.840
[Guest]: We'll sort it out.

00:36:53.840 --> 00:36:57.880
[Guest]: What they don't know is that from the court's data itself, the number of cases being filed

00:36:57.880 --> 00:36:58.880
[Guest]: in court is falling.

00:36:58.880 --> 00:37:03.480
[Guest]: Ignore criminal cases for the moment, because obviously they're a function of the population.

00:37:03.480 --> 00:37:09.240
[Guest]: Civil cases experience around the world shows as a country's population increases, as the

00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:10.240
[Guest]: economy grows, right?

00:37:10.240 --> 00:37:14.640
[Guest]: As it goes from becoming a low income to middle income and so on, the number of civil cases

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:22.240
[Guest]: increase, more transactions, more disputes, more laws, more regulation, and so on, increases

00:37:22.240 --> 00:37:25.120
[Guest]: across all levels of the judiciary.

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:30.900
[Guest]: Between I think the middle of the first decade of the 21st century and today, number of cases

00:37:30.900 --> 00:37:33.600
[Guest]: filing started plateauing, right?

00:37:33.600 --> 00:37:36.800
[Guest]: This was first noticed by three American scholars, C.T.L.

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:40.720
[Guest]: Carl Anthony, Nick Robinson, and Theodore Eisenberg, they wrote about it.

00:37:40.720 --> 00:37:41.720
[Guest]: Nobody noticed it in this country.

00:37:41.720 --> 00:37:45.600
[Guest]: I mean, they're still working on the issue, by the way, but, and I've, I've been trying

00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:46.600
[Guest]: to spread the word.

00:37:46.600 --> 00:37:49.320
[Guest]: So I decided to follow that up and see, okay, they looked at data in the early part of the

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:50.320
[Guest]: 21st century.

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:52.320
[Guest]: I thought, let me look at the latest data.

00:37:52.320 --> 00:37:56.720
[Guest]: And I wrote about this for APW, the article is still up.

00:37:56.720 --> 00:38:01.360
[Guest]: Cases filed across courts are, civil cases are falling.

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:04.760
[Amit Varma]: And that's a sign of the people's loss of trust in the judiciary.

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:05.760
[Guest]: Yes.

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:06.760
[Guest]: Yes.

00:38:06.760 --> 00:38:07.760
[Guest]: That's a sign of people voting with their feet.

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:11.760
[Guest]: They are saying, um, you know, there's no point going to court.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:17.680
[Guest]: They're saying that unless I'm put in a situation where I have absolutely no other choice, I

00:38:17.680 --> 00:38:18.680
[Guest]: will not go to court.

00:38:18.680 --> 00:38:20.240
[Guest]: This tells you the system is broken completely.

00:38:20.240 --> 00:38:21.240
[Guest]: Yes, it is.

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:27.000
[Guest]: And the problem is there is a total complacence in the higher levels of the judiciary and

00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.080
[Guest]: the legal profession that this is what it is.

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:34.520
[Guest]: Um, you know, the other day, uh, Professor Madhav Menon, who was, uh, one of the persons

00:38:34.520 --> 00:38:37.800
[Guest]: behind the founding of the national law school, still a legal loom in every way, he's like,

00:38:37.800 --> 00:38:41.240
[Guest]: why do you want to bring in all these numbers and stuff inside in the judiciary?

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:42.240
[Guest]: How does this help you?

00:38:42.240 --> 00:38:43.240
[Guest]: This is dangerous.

00:38:43.240 --> 00:38:44.240
[Guest]: What does it tell you?

00:38:44.240 --> 00:38:45.960
[Guest]: But look, look at what the numbers are telling us.

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:47.920
[Guest]: That's shocking because data tells stories.

00:38:47.920 --> 00:38:48.920
[Guest]: These are the stories.

00:38:48.920 --> 00:38:49.920
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:38:49.920 --> 00:38:50.920
[Guest]: And these are the stories.

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:51.920
[Guest]: This should be the most pressing story.

00:38:51.920 --> 00:38:56.800
[Guest]: It's not as if I dug up these numbers from some arcane corner of the country.

00:38:56.800 --> 00:38:58.520
[Guest]: It's that the Supreme court has put out these numbers.

00:38:58.520 --> 00:39:00.880
[Guest]: They are there for the public to see.

00:39:00.880 --> 00:39:04.760
[Guest]: Unfortunately, the court itself is not that interested in looking at these numbers.

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:08.920
[Guest]: Unfortunately, nobody else is really talking about it, but guys, this is what is happening.

00:39:08.920 --> 00:39:12.840
[Guest]: Uh, people are actively voting with their feet and one more to the courts.

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:16.240
[Guest]: Now you can say possibly a lot of the cases are going to tribunals, but not that many

00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:18.400
[Guest]: tribunals are there to take away that many cases.

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:22.120
[Guest]: You can say alternate dispute resolution, but that's available only to a very tiny section.

00:39:22.120 --> 00:39:26.160
[Guest]: Uh, a few years ago, Justice D Y Chandra was currently in the Supreme court when he was

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:27.160
[Guest]: a judge of the Bombay court.

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:30.800
[Guest]: He was speaking to us in a lecture and he said, you know, in, in court, I told, uh,

00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:34.080
[Guest]: parties, if there's something you can resolve by mediation, I'll refer you to mediation.

00:39:34.080 --> 00:39:37.880
[Guest]: So parties agreed, nodded, lawyers looked at each other, nodded.

00:39:37.880 --> 00:39:41.360
[Guest]: Then at the end of the day, the lawyer for another party came to his chamber and said,

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:42.360
[Guest]: yes, what is it?

00:39:42.360 --> 00:39:44.160
[Guest]: He said, sir, I have one small question for you.

00:39:44.160 --> 00:39:45.160
[Guest]: He said, yes.

00:39:45.160 --> 00:39:46.160
[Guest]: What is mediation?

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:51.240
[Guest]: So you may think it's so obvious it's there.

00:39:51.240 --> 00:39:52.880
[Guest]: Why would you use it?

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:54.880
[Guest]: Even in the legal profession, people don't know.

00:39:54.880 --> 00:39:55.880
[Guest]: This was in Bombay.

00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:58.440
[Guest]: I'm not talking about some small rural, uh, court.

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:00.080
[Guest]: This was in Bombay, in the Bombay high court.

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:02.560
[Guest]: A lawyer comes up and says, what's mediation again?

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:06.240
[Amit Varma]: So this is, this is what you point out as a problem of awareness at two levels that

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:09.480
[Amit Varma]: one, the people who actually run the judiciary aren't aware of these deep problems.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:12.880
[Amit Varma]: And perhaps in some cases, they're ignoring the data and don't take it seriously.

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:17.440
[Amit Varma]: And deeper down, even the regular legal profession, they're not as aware of it either.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:22.520
[Amit Varma]: So my question to you is that is what is needed to get us out of that 19th century mindset.

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:28.520
[Amit Varma]: Is it a cultural change or is it a change of the rules of the game?

00:40:28.520 --> 00:40:33.280
[Guest]: So one attempt is being made with the rules of the game, uh, with commercial courts, right?

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:34.280
[Guest]: Right.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:37.840
[Guest]: The idea, which if you see the law commission report, which prompted this commercial court

00:40:37.840 --> 00:40:42.080
[Guest]: law is to say that if we change the rules and people start getting used to following

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:45.300
[Guest]: these rules, it'll bring about a cultural change, right?

00:40:45.300 --> 00:40:47.560
[Guest]: That is one attempt at it.

00:40:47.560 --> 00:40:51.280
[Guest]: But I think there's a second larger attempt, which needs, which say maybe this won't be

00:40:51.280 --> 00:40:52.280
[Guest]: able to do.

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:55.080
[Guest]: They will be able to do it in the context of say civil suits and so on and so forth.

00:40:55.080 --> 00:41:01.760
[Guest]: But there's a larger cultural change needed in terms of who becomes judges, who becomes

00:41:01.760 --> 00:41:03.460
[Guest]: senior advocates and so on.

00:41:03.460 --> 00:41:05.640
[Guest]: It's still a very small pool of people.

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:08.880
[Guest]: It's a very small, self-selecting pool of people is I think the most dangerous thing

00:41:08.880 --> 00:41:09.880
[Guest]: for an institution.

00:41:09.880 --> 00:41:10.880
[Guest]: Right?

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:12.640
[Guest]: Any institution, the rules are fixed.

00:41:12.640 --> 00:41:16.080
[Guest]: The way it works is fixed and people keep coming and going.

00:41:16.080 --> 00:41:20.040
[Guest]: You know, the institution is going to die if it's the same people with the same thought

00:41:20.040 --> 00:41:24.280
[Guest]: and the same approach and have no understanding of what's happening in the outside world.

00:41:24.280 --> 00:41:29.680
[Guest]: That's unfortunately what's happening to our judiciary and the high levels of the bar.

00:41:29.680 --> 00:41:34.400
[Guest]: My one longterm project, which I hope will cause me to get contempt of court notice is

00:41:34.400 --> 00:41:39.760
[Guest]: to create a family tree of all the judges of the Supreme Court of India to see how many

00:41:39.760 --> 00:41:41.520
[Guest]: people are related to other judges.

00:41:41.520 --> 00:41:44.000
[Guest]: And I'm sure I will find a shockingly high number.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:49.280
[Guest]: I can expand that to say how many of their families, how many of their fathers, uncles,

00:41:49.280 --> 00:41:54.280
[Guest]: brothers, or even in some cases, mothers, aunts, and so on were senior advocates in

00:41:54.280 --> 00:41:55.280
[Guest]: the system.

00:41:55.280 --> 00:41:57.400
[Guest]: I'll get an even shockingly higher number.

00:41:57.400 --> 00:42:02.040
[Guest]: Some of this research is there, uh, there's an, there was a great American academic George

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:03.040
[Guest]: H. Gadbois.

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:04.400
[Guest]: His book is fantastic.

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:06.680
[Guest]: It's called the judges of the Supreme Court of India.

00:42:06.680 --> 00:42:12.960
[Guest]: He gives a brief biography of each and every judge of the Supreme Court between 50 to 89.

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:17.760
[Guest]: And the depressing outcome is that it's exactly the same kind of person who has been coming

00:42:17.760 --> 00:42:20.360
[Guest]: to the Indian judiciary since the 1950.

00:42:20.360 --> 00:42:21.960
[Guest]: And what will change this?

00:42:21.960 --> 00:42:25.040
[Guest]: What will change this is changing that.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:26.520
[Guest]: So two ways to change this.

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:29.000
[Guest]: One is that the profession widens, right?

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:31.960
[Guest]: Uh, the profession widens so that paths to success are more.

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:35.360
[Guest]: It's not that you survive for 10 years and therefore you succeed, which means depending

00:42:35.360 --> 00:42:36.360
[Amit Varma]: on your parents.

00:42:36.360 --> 00:42:40.160
[Amit Varma]: Can any law graduate in the country today hope to become chief justice of the Supreme

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:44.760
[Amit Varma]: Court someday, or is it only a privileged few because of the background and so who have

00:42:44.760 --> 00:42:47.280
[Amit Varma]: that clear path?

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:51.200
[Guest]: Chief justice of India, surprisingly has been fairly diverse, right?

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:56.640
[Guest]: We have had a justice Kapadia who started as a law clerk, I mean a clerk of a lawyer,

00:42:56.640 --> 00:43:00.760
[Guest]: not even a law clerk, a clerk of a lawyer to become a chief justice of India.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:06.440
[Guest]: We've had a justice Satasivam who was the first in his village to complete an education

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:09.880
[Guest]: who has gone on to become the chief justice of India.

00:43:09.880 --> 00:43:14.160
[Guest]: Um, we have had people who have overcome difficulties to become the chief justice of India, but

00:43:14.160 --> 00:43:16.360
[Guest]: there it's a selection, right?

00:43:16.360 --> 00:43:20.380
[Guest]: At that point you're like, I want this person, somebody somewhere has decided, I want this

00:43:20.380 --> 00:43:23.800
[Guest]: person to become a chief justice, but we're talking about the larger system.

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:27.520
[Guest]: I'm talking about the fact that currently there are about 700 judges at the high court

00:43:27.520 --> 00:43:30.600
[Guest]: and Supreme Court level and many more below them.

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:33.100
[Guest]: The problem is there is a glass ceiling.

00:43:33.100 --> 00:43:37.480
[Guest]: The glass ceiling is that actually the lowest level is the most diverse in the lowest level.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:39.360
[Guest]: States have implemented reservations.

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:41.600
[Guest]: More women are present in the judiciary.

00:43:41.600 --> 00:43:44.760
[Guest]: You have a wider representation of sections of society.

00:43:44.760 --> 00:43:50.080
[Guest]: But because the next level you, it depends on the discretion of about five, usually men,

00:43:50.080 --> 00:43:53.120
[Guest]: five to six men, they choose people like that.

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:56.640
[Guest]: So their prejudices perpetuate themselves through generations and you have those guys

00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:58.480
[Guest]: rising through the system.

00:43:58.480 --> 00:44:07.800
[Guest]: So one way to undo this is to what the government tried and botched very badly in 2014 is to

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:10.320
[Guest]: change the appointment mechanism.

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:16.080
[Guest]: What they tried to do was to say, was to take the tangent of the issue on a completely different

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:17.080
[Guest]: pattern.

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:18.080
[Guest]: It should be the government or the judiciary.

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:19.800
[Guest]: Actually, that's not the problem.

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:23.880
[Guest]: The problem is who are the people who are being appointed, right?

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:29.120
[Guest]: It honestly to me doesn't matter anymore if it is three judges or five judges and three

00:44:29.120 --> 00:44:31.280
[Guest]: government or three judges and five government.

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.580
[Guest]: It does not.

00:44:32.580 --> 00:44:38.720
[Guest]: You need to be able to say, we want a judiciary which will cater to a wider section of people,

00:44:38.720 --> 00:44:45.200
[Guest]: which will ensure that, you know, people are, have a shot at being judges of the high court

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:49.200
[Guest]: and even the Supreme Court, irrespective of whether they were the sons or daughters of

00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:50.900
[Guest]: famous lawyers.

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:54.480
[Guest]: And if they have worked their way through the system, a high court position should be

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:59.400
[Guest]: a reward for them or not a reward, it should not be a reward, should be a right to them,

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:00.400
[Guest]: right?

00:45:00.400 --> 00:45:04.680
[Guest]: So it should become, I think, a rule that the 10 best performing judges every year become

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:07.000
[Guest]: high court judges, right?

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:10.960
[Guest]: At the lower level, you will instantly solve capacity problems that I mean, people will

00:45:10.960 --> 00:45:11.960
[Guest]: keep raising issues.

00:45:11.960 --> 00:45:13.680
[Guest]: They're not good enough, or they could be much better.

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:18.240
[Guest]: I mean, this is going to be there, but if you're not going to make any effort at improving

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:22.480
[Guest]: the quality of the subordinate judiciary, you're going to be stuck with the small elite

00:45:22.480 --> 00:45:26.880
[Guest]: of people becoming judges again and again, their children becoming judges, their friends

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:29.920
[Guest]: becoming judges, their chamber mates becoming judges.

00:45:29.920 --> 00:45:33.120
[Guest]: And you'll be stuck with this elite, which, which loses touch with what's happening.

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:36.640
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, one of the best books I've read in recent years, Super Forecasting by Philip

00:45:36.640 --> 00:45:42.120
[Amit Varma]: Tetlock has a chapter about how diversity leads to better decision making, which study

00:45:42.120 --> 00:45:46.760
[Amit Varma]: after study has shown that even diversity for its own sake will lead to better decision

00:45:46.760 --> 00:45:49.400
[Amit Varma]: making more than any other factor.

00:45:49.400 --> 00:45:52.600
[Amit Varma]: And when you talk about the judiciary, where decision making is essentially everything,

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:57.560
[Amit Varma]: exactly, it's, it's mind boggling that we actually have a system that works the other

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:58.560
[Guest]: way.

00:45:58.560 --> 00:45:59.560
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:03.840
[Guest]: And, uh, you need this kind of diversity in terms of representing India's diversity.

00:46:03.840 --> 00:46:08.480
[Guest]: I mean, they maintain diversity in the way that you will have 25% from South, 25% from

00:46:08.480 --> 00:46:09.480
[Guest]: West, East and North.

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:11.040
[Amit Varma]: That's the only diversity that's maintained.

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:14.640
[Amit Varma]: It sounds like cricket back in the day.

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:19.160
[Guest]: This is actually empirically shown by George Gatbois in his book between the 40 years,

00:46:19.160 --> 00:46:22.920
[Guest]: the appointment mechanism has ensured that there is a roughly equal representation from

00:46:22.920 --> 00:46:25.680
[Guest]: the four broad regions of India.

00:46:25.680 --> 00:46:29.040
[Guest]: But you want diversity in terms of caste, you want diversity in terms of class, you

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:32.840
[Guest]: want diversity in terms of gender, you want diversity in terms of people with different

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:33.920
[Guest]: life experiences.

00:46:33.920 --> 00:46:35.380
[Guest]: People are first generation lawyers.

00:46:35.380 --> 00:46:37.760
[Guest]: People are first generation graduates.

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:41.280
[Guest]: And unfortunately we're not even thinking on those lines in the system.

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:43.880
[Guest]: It's still becoming a very self-serving, selecting elite.

00:46:43.880 --> 00:46:48.880
[Guest]: And that sort of shows in the way in which they're not thinking about the institution

00:46:48.880 --> 00:46:49.880
[Guest]: at all.

00:46:49.880 --> 00:46:50.880
[Guest]: Right.

00:46:50.880 --> 00:46:55.160
[Guest]: Uh, you, we are now in a system where each year justice is like, I have one year for

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:56.160
[Guest]: retirement.

00:46:56.160 --> 00:46:57.160
[Guest]: Let me just pass this out.

00:46:57.160 --> 00:47:01.600
[Guest]: The third major controversy, no, there's no trust within the system to let's change these

00:47:01.600 --> 00:47:02.840
[Guest]: things.

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:03.840
[Guest]: Right.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:05.040
[Guest]: It's become like, Oh, I have settled into this.

00:47:05.040 --> 00:47:06.480
[Guest]: I have one more year of retirement.

00:47:06.480 --> 00:47:11.640
[Amit Varma]: I will quietly pass this through and let's hope nothing happens to actually bring about

00:47:11.640 --> 00:47:16.960
[Amit Varma]: change is a cultural one where the people who are running the system want to do it.

00:47:16.960 --> 00:47:19.040
[Amit Varma]: And therefore they change the rules of the game.

00:47:19.040 --> 00:47:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And our problem sort of is that because you don't have enough diversity of thought or

00:47:22.760 --> 00:47:27.440
[Amit Varma]: diversity of representation, you have the same little narrow clique out there who are

00:47:27.440 --> 00:47:31.000
[Amit Varma]: just content to, you know, let their time go by.

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:35.360
[Amit Varma]: So now tell me something very often in other fields, like I've done so many episodes on

00:47:35.360 --> 00:47:39.040
[Amit Varma]: different aspects of public policy and the question always comes back to, okay, so what

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:40.600
[Amit Varma]: can the government do to change this?

00:47:40.600 --> 00:47:42.440
[Amit Varma]: And how do you get the government to change this?

00:47:42.440 --> 00:47:47.280
[Amit Varma]: But it's a, it's a given that the judiciaries should fundamentally be autonomous.

00:47:47.280 --> 00:47:49.360
[Amit Varma]: Is this an area where the government even has a role?

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:50.360
[Guest]: Yes.

00:47:50.360 --> 00:47:54.040
[Guest]: I think the government has a role, but unfortunately the government has approached this in a bad

00:47:54.040 --> 00:47:55.040
[Guest]: faith way.

00:47:55.040 --> 00:47:56.040
[Guest]: Right.

00:47:56.040 --> 00:48:01.280
[Guest]: So the unfortunate history of government judiciary relations in independent India has been a

00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:05.960
[Guest]: mutual bad faith relationship where the judiciary suspects and has put these barriers in place

00:48:05.960 --> 00:48:09.920
[Guest]: to prevent government intervention and government intervenes to say, now we want to be able

00:48:09.920 --> 00:48:10.920
[Guest]: to control you guys.

00:48:10.920 --> 00:48:13.800
[Unknown]: So it's been an antagonistic, antagonistic thing.

00:48:13.800 --> 00:48:18.200
[Guest]: And in fact, the relationship is supposed to be antagonistic, but not in this way, not

00:48:18.200 --> 00:48:19.200
[Guest]: in a bad faith way.

00:48:19.200 --> 00:48:21.320
[Guest]: You're supposed to be able to say what you're doing is not right.

00:48:21.320 --> 00:48:25.000
[Guest]: And it's supposed to be able to say, we are also a check on you, but not in the sense

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:29.200
[Guest]: of, I want to control you or I'm going to treat everything you do with suspicion.

00:48:29.200 --> 00:48:32.840
[Guest]: That is not the kind of antagonism that we want.

00:48:32.840 --> 00:48:33.840
[Guest]: It's difficult.

00:48:33.840 --> 00:48:37.120
[Guest]: It is going to be difficult for the government to test it and tell the judiciary what needs

00:48:37.120 --> 00:48:38.520
[Guest]: to be done.

00:48:38.520 --> 00:48:45.360
[Guest]: It has to be the best that the government can do is to sort of play a facilitative role.

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:46.360
[Guest]: Right.

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:52.400
[Guest]: And one of the ways is to say that, guys, please accept this reality.

00:48:52.400 --> 00:48:53.640
[Guest]: Okay.

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:56.920
[Guest]: We want things to change and we'll help you make the change.

00:48:56.920 --> 00:48:57.920
[Guest]: It's not as if that's not impossible.

00:48:57.920 --> 00:48:59.280
[Guest]: But they can't mandate the change.

00:48:59.280 --> 00:49:00.280
[Guest]: They can't mandate the change.

00:49:00.280 --> 00:49:01.280
[Guest]: They can't.

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:02.280
[Guest]: That's the thing that you can't mandate the change.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:03.280
[Amit Varma]: Which is a good thing.

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:04.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:49:04.280 --> 00:49:05.280
[Guest]: Which is the good thing.

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:11.200
[Guest]: What the, and I would think that the NJSC case or the NJSC saga would have happened

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:16.760
[Guest]: very differently if the government and good faith had said, we want to hold consultations

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:17.760
[Guest]: with the judiciary.

00:49:17.760 --> 00:49:18.760
[Amit Varma]: Give me your TLDR.

00:49:18.760 --> 00:49:19.760
[Guest]: What saga?

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:20.760
[Guest]: What case?

00:49:20.760 --> 00:49:22.160
[Guest]: I'm talking about the judicial appointments commission where the Supreme Court struck

00:49:22.160 --> 00:49:25.960
[Guest]: down the constitutional amendment to say that we're adding a law minister to the appointment

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:27.560
[Amit Varma]: process and so on and so forth.

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:28.560
[Amit Varma]: Sure.

00:49:28.560 --> 00:49:29.560
[Guest]: Right.

00:49:29.560 --> 00:49:34.240
[Amit Varma]: If the government had said, and I'm not saying this, this government did it badly, that essentially

00:49:34.240 --> 00:49:35.240
[Amit Varma]: the same government.

00:49:35.240 --> 00:49:36.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:49:36.240 --> 00:49:37.240
[Guest]: It was, the idea itself was very flawed.

00:49:37.240 --> 00:49:38.240
[Guest]: When you said, okay, we'll come up with this bill.

00:49:38.240 --> 00:49:39.240
[Guest]: We'll pass it in parliament.

00:49:39.240 --> 00:49:42.240
[Guest]: We'll amend the constitution and everything will be fine.

00:49:42.240 --> 00:49:47.000
[Guest]: If you had said, taken a draft of the judiciary and said, guys, we think this needs to change.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:49.080
[Guest]: And it's not because we want to control you.

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:52.560
[Guest]: We think that there is some issue with the way in which appointments is happening and

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:55.000
[Guest]: we were considering how best to address it.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:49:56.000
[Guest]: We have an idea.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:57.080
[Guest]: What do you think can be done?

00:49:57.080 --> 00:50:01.520
[Guest]: I think you would have had a very different reaction because the experience of lawmaking

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:05.760
[Guest]: in India shows that the more you involve stakeholders, the more robust that law will be.

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:06.760
[Guest]: Right.

00:50:06.760 --> 00:50:10.280
[Guest]: And the judiciary here is the stakeholder in a law when it comes to appointments.

00:50:10.280 --> 00:50:13.340
[Guest]: When you sort of shut them out of the process and said, huh, we'll pass a bill.

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:15.400
[Guest]: You better follow it in the future.

00:50:15.400 --> 00:50:17.660
[Guest]: You're going to get a reaction to it as well.

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:21.080
[Guest]: So, which is why I think that is what the government's role should be.

00:50:21.080 --> 00:50:25.800
[Guest]: The government's role really should be, look, it's easy to write checks, right?

00:50:25.800 --> 00:50:30.360
[Guest]: The judiciary pretty much gets what it's, get it, get what gets what it wants.

00:50:30.360 --> 00:50:33.880
[Guest]: And half the time it's not able to spend it because they're not trained in how to run

00:50:33.880 --> 00:50:34.880
[Guest]: an institution.

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:35.880
[Guest]: Right.

00:50:35.880 --> 00:50:38.560
[Guest]: We, judges end up becoming judges because they're successful lawyers.

00:50:38.560 --> 00:50:43.680
[Guest]: At most they may have managed a office of 10 people or 15 people, not a sprawling institution

00:50:43.680 --> 00:50:47.560
[Guest]: of the size of even say the Karnataka high court or any, any average high court, I think

00:50:47.560 --> 00:50:48.560
[Guest]: has hundreds of employees.

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:49.560
[Guest]: Right.

00:50:49.560 --> 00:50:50.560
[Amit Varma]: I'm not talking about the really tiny ones.

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:53.800
[Guest]: So they haven't even evolved mechanisms of how to do this kind of internal management.

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:54.800
[Guest]: They don't.

00:50:54.800 --> 00:50:58.640
[Guest]: And they don't have the training or the understanding of how to manage this body.

00:50:58.640 --> 00:51:00.280
[Guest]: They learn on the job.

00:51:00.280 --> 00:51:01.280
[Guest]: Some of them do a good job.

00:51:01.280 --> 00:51:02.560
[Guest]: Some of them don't do a good job.

00:51:02.560 --> 00:51:06.360
[Guest]: But I think there needs to be that awareness of the judges as well as say, okay, look,

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:08.080
[Guest]: you know, our role has changed.

00:51:08.080 --> 00:51:11.600
[Guest]: We're not just the guys who come to court at nine o'clock in the morning and leave at

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:14.460
[Guest]: six in the morning, having spent the bulk of our day deciding cases.

00:51:14.460 --> 00:51:17.540
[Guest]: We are running this institution and we're in charge of running this institution.

00:51:17.540 --> 00:51:21.520
[Guest]: So we need to put in place mechanisms that make it easier for us to run this institution.

00:51:21.520 --> 00:51:24.640
[Guest]: We can't just rely on our administrative staff, figuring out how to do things when we give

00:51:24.640 --> 00:51:27.760
[Guest]: these grand pronouncements and then they're hoping things work out.

00:51:27.760 --> 00:51:31.360
[Guest]: So there needs to be that level of acknowledgement as well.

00:51:31.360 --> 00:51:34.440
[Guest]: And the government sort of saying, we're here to help you, right?

00:51:34.440 --> 00:51:37.040
[Guest]: You figure out, you know, what would work for you best and we're here.

00:51:37.040 --> 00:51:39.840
[Guest]: So the government can at best play a facilitative role.

00:51:39.840 --> 00:51:43.440
[Guest]: But I still think the pressure for the change will come bottom up.

00:51:43.440 --> 00:51:48.120
[Guest]: The pressure to change will come bottom up when, you know, lawyers start realizing that

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:50.400
[Guest]: nobody's coming to us anymore, right?

00:51:50.400 --> 00:51:56.320
[Guest]: Our profession is increasingly becoming irrelevant and that we are, yes, we have these few highly

00:51:56.320 --> 00:52:00.800
[Guest]: important cases are a few highly important stuff, but at the end of the day, our profession

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:05.800
[Guest]: no longer enjoys the kind of respect or the kind of dignity that other professions are

00:52:05.800 --> 00:52:12.440
[Guest]: handed that people are conscious that even the smart, talented young people leaving law

00:52:12.440 --> 00:52:13.640
[Guest]: colleges are saying, thank you.

00:52:13.640 --> 00:52:18.360
[Guest]: I'd rather go to a law firm and work for a corporate or work for an NGO or work in policy

00:52:18.360 --> 00:52:20.320
[Guest]: than come to the court and decide to be this thing.

00:52:20.320 --> 00:52:24.800
[Guest]: So when they see that, you know, hang on, our profession is literally dying at the roots,

00:52:24.800 --> 00:52:29.480
[Guest]: that is when I think there will be some pressure to, you know, push the thing forward.

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:31.640
[Amit Varma]: So this has been a very illuminating conversation.

00:52:31.640 --> 00:52:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Let me end by asking you two questions.

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:39.560
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, that one, what makes you hopeful about the judiciary in India and things changing

00:52:39.560 --> 00:52:40.840
[Amit Varma]: for the better and so on?

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:42.000
[Amit Varma]: And two, what makes you despair?

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:43.960
[Amit Varma]: In fact, let's, let's talk of the despair.

00:52:43.960 --> 00:52:44.960
[Guest]: Sure.

00:52:44.960 --> 00:52:48.440
[Guest]: Um, what, what, what makes me despair is to sort of see the state of the higher judicial

00:52:48.440 --> 00:52:52.120
[Guest]: institutions, the state of the high courts in the country and the Supreme court.

00:52:52.120 --> 00:52:56.640
[Guest]: Uh, the fact, I mean, whatever the news yesterday, three judge bench says other three judge bench

00:52:56.640 --> 00:52:58.960
[Guest]: was wrong and saying every judgment is wrong.

00:52:58.960 --> 00:53:04.400
[Guest]: I was going like, Oh my God, do you guys just realize how idiotic you sound?

00:53:04.400 --> 00:53:05.400
[Guest]: It's a part of a bigger issue.

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:09.240
[Guest]: I mean, we can go into the niceties of who was right and who was wrong, but you, you

00:53:09.240 --> 00:53:14.680
[Guest]: see that there is a complete and total breakdown of trust within the institution that as an

00:53:14.680 --> 00:53:16.200
[Guest]: institution you have stopped functioning.

00:53:16.200 --> 00:53:19.800
[Guest]: You're just a bunch of judges sitting there and doing things.

00:53:19.800 --> 00:53:22.160
[Guest]: What gives me hope is actually the lowest level.

00:53:22.160 --> 00:53:26.760
[Guest]: What gives me hope is that on a daily basis, yes, you may say that they're slow, they're

00:53:26.760 --> 00:53:31.600
[Guest]: inefficient, they're terrible, but your civil rights and my civil rights are being defended

00:53:31.600 --> 00:53:36.640
[Guest]: by the guys at the lowest level, by the magistrates, by the civil judge, junior division, senior

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:38.400
[Guest]: civil judge, senior decision.

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:42.440
[Guest]: They're the ones who do the painstaking task of conducting a trial.

00:53:42.440 --> 00:53:46.120
[Guest]: They're the ones who ensure that everybody gets a fair hearing.

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:50.200
[Guest]: They're the ones working in the worst possible conditions, but still, you know, inspiring

00:53:50.200 --> 00:53:55.360
[Guest]: sufficient confidence that, okay, you can at least trust them to this extent.

00:53:55.360 --> 00:53:58.920
[Guest]: They're still doing the thing in terrible condition and in horrible condition, but they

00:53:58.920 --> 00:53:59.920
[Guest]: still turn up.

00:53:59.920 --> 00:54:00.920
[Guest]: They do their job.

00:54:00.920 --> 00:54:04.800
[Guest]: You still have judges like judge Ajmeet Singh, who in the face of enormous pressure in the

00:54:04.800 --> 00:54:07.260
[Guest]: Ram Rahim case decided correctly.

00:54:07.260 --> 00:54:13.960
[Guest]: You have a judge like the Sousa, the Karnataka high court judge in the face of such enormous

00:54:13.960 --> 00:54:19.040
[Guest]: pressure over Jai Jalilitta, fantastic judgment, just did his job right.

00:54:19.040 --> 00:54:22.720
[Guest]: You just need, and there are people who are just doing their jobs and that's really what

00:54:22.720 --> 00:54:25.040
[Guest]: we need more of.

00:54:25.040 --> 00:54:26.040
[Guest]: So that gives me hope.

00:54:26.040 --> 00:54:32.480
[Guest]: But it also gives me hope is the fact that at least with the law schools in the picture

00:54:32.480 --> 00:54:36.840
[Guest]: and the fact that even the private law colleges are pushing to improve the standards and so

00:54:36.840 --> 00:54:37.840
[Amit Varma]: on.

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:40.760
[Guest]: The supply of good lawyers, the supply of good lawyers is going up.

00:54:40.760 --> 00:54:46.400
[Guest]: That more and more people are choosing law because they see a future for themselves in

00:54:46.400 --> 00:54:49.920
[Guest]: the profession that they see that, yes, you know, there's something good that can come

00:54:49.920 --> 00:54:50.920
[Guest]: out of this.

00:54:50.920 --> 00:54:55.760
[Guest]: Uh, we are seeing that people are seeing that the law is not just a 19th century institution,

00:54:55.760 --> 00:54:59.500
[Guest]: which we are stuck with somehow, but we need to bring it into the 21st century.

00:54:59.500 --> 00:55:02.720
[Guest]: So we're having more informed conversations about the law I see.

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:06.200
[Guest]: And people may say this is negative, but I see this as a necessary positive.

00:55:06.200 --> 00:55:09.160
[Guest]: The courts are being covered like never before, right?

00:55:09.160 --> 00:55:13.120
[Guest]: I would like our newspaper to do 10 X, but I think we're doing 10 X of what we were doing

00:55:13.120 --> 00:55:14.480
[Guest]: two decades ago.

00:55:14.480 --> 00:55:18.120
[Guest]: Um, today people are live tweeting from the courts.

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:20.120
[Guest]: People are following what order was passed.

00:55:20.120 --> 00:55:24.640
[Guest]: People are following cases, you know, with great interest, understanding issues, knowing

00:55:24.640 --> 00:55:26.920
[Guest]: this is how courts work and they want more.

00:55:26.920 --> 00:55:31.600
[Guest]: And I think at the end of the day, the court's credibility as an institution rests on only

00:55:31.600 --> 00:55:32.600
[Guest]: one thing.

00:55:32.600 --> 00:55:33.960
[Guest]: Forget everything else.

00:55:33.960 --> 00:55:38.360
[Guest]: It rests on the fact that it's the only institution that today you can go and see how it functions.

00:55:38.360 --> 00:55:41.240
[Guest]: You can't walk into a bureaucrat's office, you can't examine their files unless you follow

00:55:41.240 --> 00:55:42.240
[Guest]: a very detailed procedure.

00:55:42.240 --> 00:55:44.560
[Guest]: You're not allowed to enter into parliament.

00:55:44.560 --> 00:55:48.600
[Guest]: And you know, unless until we got television, nobody knew what was exactly happening in

00:55:48.600 --> 00:55:49.600
[Amit Varma]: parliament.

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:52.800
[Amit Varma]: So to some extent, improving the judiciary, the onus is on us as citizens, because this

00:55:52.800 --> 00:55:55.720
[Guest]: is the one institution which is actually transparent, transparent.

00:55:55.720 --> 00:55:56.720
[Guest]: Yes.

00:55:56.720 --> 00:56:00.440
[Guest]: So, uh, and there are of course issues of how to make sense of judgments and yes, our

00:56:00.440 --> 00:56:03.040
[Guest]: courts are covered and all of that, but you can see it working.

00:56:03.040 --> 00:56:06.040
[Guest]: The public can go and see it work and the litigant can go and see it working.

00:56:06.040 --> 00:56:10.440
[Guest]: And I think the more scrutiny there is, and you don't, you don't just leave it to the

00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:13.720
[Guest]: lawyers and litigants to scrutinize the courts, you leave it to the general public to scrutinize

00:56:13.720 --> 00:56:14.720
[Guest]: the courts.

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:17.200
[Guest]: The more people scrutinize the courts, the more people say, Hey, this is not working

00:56:17.200 --> 00:56:19.160
[Guest]: or something is seriously going wrong.

00:56:19.160 --> 00:56:20.440
[Guest]: I think that's what gives me hope.

00:56:20.440 --> 00:56:24.280
[Guest]: That's what gives me hope that there'll be enough pressure put on the fact that on the

00:56:24.280 --> 00:56:27.040
[Guest]: judges on the lawyers and everybody else that something needs to be done.

00:56:27.040 --> 00:56:29.200
[Amit Varma]: That's a hopeful and inspiring note to end on.

00:56:29.200 --> 00:56:31.480
[Amit Varma]: We don't just have to lament the state of the judiciary.

00:56:31.480 --> 00:56:33.160
[Amit Varma]: We can be part of the change.

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:34.160
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

